en|Copyright infringement (at times referred to as piracy) is the use of works protected by
en|copyright without permission for a usage where such permission is required, thereby infringing certain exclusive
en|rights granted to the copyright holder, such as the right to reproduce, distribute, display or
en|perform the protected work, or to make derivative works. The copyright holder is typically the
en|work's creator, or a publisher or other business to whom copyright has been assigned. Copyright
en|holders routinely invoke legal and technological measures to prevent and penalize copyright infringement. Copyright infringement
en|disputes are usually resolved through direct negotiation, a notice and take down process, or litigation
en|in civil court. Egregious or large-scale commercial infringement, especially when it involves counterfeiting, is sometimes
en|prosecuted via the criminal justice system. Shifting public expectations, advances in digital technology and the
en|increasing reach of the Internet have led to such widespread, anonymous infringement that copyright-dependent industries
en|now focus less on pursuing individuals who seek and share copyright-protected content online, and more
en|on expanding copyright law to recognize and penalize, as indirect infringers, the service providers and
en|software distributors who are said to facilitate and encourage individual acts of infringement by others.
en|Estimates of the actual economic impact of copyright infringement vary widely and depend on other
en|factors. Nevertheless, copyright holders, industry representatives, and legislators have long characterized copyright infringement as piracy
en|or theft – language which some U.S. courts now regard as pejorative or otherwise contentious.
en|Terminology The terms piracy and theft are often associated with copyright infringement. The original meaning
en|of piracy is "robbery or illegal violence at sea", but the term has been in
en|use for centuries as a synonym for acts of copyright infringement. Theft, meanwhile, emphasizes the
en|potential commercial harm of infringement to copyright holders. However, copyright is a type of intellectual
en|property, an area of law distinct from that which covers robbery or theft, offenses related
en|only to tangible property. Not all copyright infringement results in commercial loss, and the U.S.
en|Supreme Court ruled in 1985 that infringement does not easily equate with theft.This was taken
en|further in the case MPAA v. Hotfile, where Judge Kathleen M. Williams granted a motion
en|to deny the MPAA the usage of words whose appearance was primarily "pejorative". This list
en|included the word "piracy", the use of which, the motion by the defense stated, serves
en|no court purpose but to misguide and inflame the jury. = "Piracy" = The term
en|"piracy" has been used to refer to the unauthorized copying, distribution and selling of works
en|in copyright. In 1668 publisher John Hancock wrote of "some dishonest Booksellers, called Land-Pirats, who
en|make it their practise to steal Impressions of other mens Copies" in the work A
en|String of Pearls: or, The Best Things Reserved till Last by Thomas Brooks. Over time
en|the metaphor mostly used in the book-trade became more common, such that the use of
en|the word 'pirate' itself to describe unauthorized publishing of books was attested to in Nathan
en|Bailey's 1736 dictionary An Universal Etymological English Dictionary: 'One who lives by pillage and robbing
en|on the sea. Also a plagiary' The practice of labeling the infringement of exclusive rights
en|in creative works as "piracy" predates statutory copyright law. Prior to the Statute of Anne
en|in 1710, the Stationers' Company of London in 1557, received a royal charter giving the
en|company a monopoly on publication and tasking it with enforcing the charter. Article 61 of
en|the 1994 Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPs) requires criminal procedures and
en|penalties in cases of "willful trademark counterfeiting or copyright piracy on a commercial scale." Piracy
en|traditionally refers to acts of copyright infringement intentionally committed for financial gain, though more recently,
en|copyright holders have described online copyright infringement, particularly in relation to peer-to-peer file sharing networks,
en|as "piracy".Richard Stallman and the GNU Project have criticized the use of the word "piracy"
en|in these situations, saying that publishers use the word to refer to "copying they don't
en|approve of" and that "they [publishers] imply that it is ethically equivalent to attacking ships
en|on the high seas, kidnapping and murdering the people on them." = "Theft" = Copyright
en|holders frequently refer to copyright infringement as theft, "although such misuse has been rejected by
en|legislatures and courts". The slogan "Piracy is theft" was used beginning in the 1980s, and
en|is still being used. In copyright law, infringement does not refer to theft of physical
en|objects that take away the owner's possession, but an instance where a person exercises one
en|of the exclusive rights of the copyright holder without authorization. Courts have distinguished between copyright
en|infringement and theft. For instance, the United States Supreme Court held in Dowling v. United
en|States (1985) that bootleg phonorecords did not constitute stolen property. Instead, interference with copyright does
en|not easily equate with theft, conversion, or fraud. The Copyright Act even employs a separate
en|term of art to define one who misappropriates a copyright: '[...] an infringer of the
en|copyright.' The court said that in the case of copyright infringement, the province guaranteed to
en|the copyright holder by copyright law – certain exclusive rights – is invaded, but no
en|control, physical or otherwise, is taken over the copyright, nor is the copyright holder wholly
en|deprived of using the copyrighted work or exercising the exclusive rights held. = "Freebooting" =
en|The term "freebooting" has been used to describe the unauthorized copying of online media, particularly
en|videos, onto websites such as Facebook, YouTube or Twitter. The word itself had already been
en|in use since the 16th century, referring to pirates, and meant "looting" or "plundering". This
en|form of the word – a portmanteau of "freeloading" and "bootlegging" – was suggested by
en|YouTuber and podcaster Brady Haran in the podcast Hello Internet. Haran advocated the term in
en|an attempt to find a phrase more emotive than "copyright infringement", yet more appropriate than
en|"theft". Motivation Some of the motives for engaging in copyright infringement are the following: Pricing
en|– unwillingness or inability to pay the price requested by the legitimate sellers Testing and
en|evaluation – try before paying for what may be bad value Unavailability – no legitimate
en|sellers providing the product in the language or country of the end-user: not yet launched
en|there, already withdrawn from sales, never to be sold there, geographical restrictions on online distribution
en|and international shipping Usefulness – the legitimate product comes with various means (DRM, region lock,
en|DVD region code, Blu-ray region code) of restricting legitimate use (backups, usage on devices of
en|different vendors, offline usage) or comes with non-skippable advertisements and anti-piracy disclaimers, which are removed
en|in the unauthorized product, making it more desirable for the end-user Shopping experience – no
en|legitimate sellers providing the product with the required quality through online distribution and through a
en|shopping system with the required level of user-friendliness Anonymity – downloading works does not require
en|identification whereas downloads directly from the website of the copyright owner often require a valid
en|email address and/or other credentials Freedom of information – opposition to copyright law in generalSometimes
en|only partial compliance with license agreements is the cause. For example, in 2013, the US
en|Army settled a lawsuit with Texas-based company Apptricity which makes software that allows the army
en|to track their soldiers in real time. In 2004, the US Army paid the company
en|a total of $4.5 million for a license of 500 users while allegedly installing the
en|software for more than 9000 users; the case was settled for US$50 million. Major anti-piracy
en|organizations, like the BSA, conduct software licensing audits regularly to ensure full compliance.Cara Cusumano, director
en|of the Tribeca Film Festival, stated in April 2014: "Piracy is less about people not
en|wanting to pay and more about just wanting the immediacy – people saying, 'I want
en|to watch Spiderman right now' and downloading it". The statement occurred during the third year
en|that the festival used the Internet to present its content, while it was the first
en|year that it featured a showcase of content producers who work exclusively online. Cusumano further
en|explained that downloading behavior is not merely conducted by people who merely want to obtain
en|content for free: I think that if companies were willing to put that material out
en|there, moving forward, consumers will follow. It's just that [consumers] want to consume films online
en|and they're ready to consume films that way and we're not necessarily offering them in
en|that way. So it's the distribution models that need to catch up. People will pay
en|for the content. In response to Cusumano's perspective, Screen Producers Australia executive director Matt Deaner
en|clarified the motivation of the film industry: "Distributors are usually wanting to encourage cinema-going as
en|part of this process [of monetizing through returns] and restrict the immediate access to online
en|so as to encourage the maximum number of people to go to the cinema." Deaner
en|further explained the matter in terms of the Australian film industry, stating: "there are currently
en|restrictions on quantities of tax support that a film can receive unless the film has
en|a traditional cinema release."In a study published in the Journal of Behavioural and Experimental Economics,
en|and reported on in early May 2014, researchers from the University of Portsmouth in the
en|UK discussed findings from examining the illegal downloading behavior of 6,000 Finnish people, aged seven
en|to 84. The list of reasons for downloading given by the study respondents included money
en|saving; the ability to access material not on general release, or before it was released;
en|and assisting artists to avoid involvement with record companies and movie studios.In a public talk
en|between Bill Gates, Warren Buffett, and Brent Schlender at the University of Washington in 1998,
en|Bill Gates commented on piracy as a means to an end, whereby people who use
en|Microsoft software illegally will eventually pay for it, out of familiarity, as a country's economy
en|develops and legitimate products become more affordable to businesses and consumers: Although about three million
en|computers get sold every year in China, people don't pay for the software. Someday they
en|will, though. And as long as they're going to steal it, we want them to
en|steal ours. They'll get sort of addicted, and then we'll somehow figure out how to
en|collect sometime in the next decade. = Developing world = In Media Piracy in Emerging
en|Economies, the first independent comparative study of media piracy focused on Brazil, India, Russia, South
en|Africa, Mexico, Turkey and Bolivia, "high prices for media goods, low incomes, and cheap digital
en|technologies" are the chief factors that lead to the global spread of media piracy, especially
en|in emerging markets. According to the study, even though digital piracy inflicts additional costs on
en|the production side of media, it also offers the main access to media goods in
en|developing countries. The strong tradeoffs that favor using digital piracy in developing economies dictate the
en|current neglected law enforcement's toward digital piracy.In China as of 2013, the issue of digital
en|infringement has not merely been legal, but social – originating from the high demand for
en|cheap and affordable goods as well as the governmental connections of the businesses which produce
en|such goods. = Motivations due to censorship = There have been instances where a country's
en|government bans a movie, resulting in the spread of copied videos and DVDs. Romanian-born documentary
en|maker Ilinca Calugareanu wrote a New York Times article telling the story of Irina Margareta
en|Nistor, a narrator for state TV under Nicolae Ceauşescu's regime. A visitor from the west
en|gave her bootlegged copies of American movies, which she dubbed for secret viewings through Romania.
en|According to the article, she dubbed more than 3,000 movies and became the country's second-most
en|famous voice after Ceauşescu, even though no one knew her name until many years later.
en|Existing and proposed laws Most countries extend copyright protections to authors of works. In countries
en|with copyright legislation, enforcement of copyright is generally the responsibility of the copyright holder. However,
en|in several jurisdictions there are also criminal penalties for copyright infringement. According to the U.S.
en|Chamber of Commerce's 2021 IP Index, the nations with the lowest scores for copyright protection
en|were Vietnam, Pakistan, Egypt, Nigeria, Brunei, Algeria, Venezuela and Argentina. = Civil law = Copyright
en|infringement in civil law is any violation of the exclusive rights of the owner. In
en|U.S. law, those rights include reproduction, the preparation of derivative works, distributing copies by sale
en|or rental, and public performance or display.In the U.S., copyright infringement is sometimes confronted via
en|lawsuits in civil court, against alleged infringers directly or against providers of services and software
en|that support unauthorized copying. For example, major motion-picture corporation MGM Studios filed suit against P2P
en|file-sharing services Grokster and Streamcast for their contributory role in copyright infringement. In 2005, the
en|Supreme Court ruled in favor of MGM, holding that such services could be held liable
en|for copyright infringement since they functioned and, indeed, willfully marketed themselves as venues for acquiring
en|copyrighted movies. The MGM v. Grokster case did not overturn the earlier Sony v. Universal
en|City Studios decision, but rather clouded the legal waters; future designers of software capable of
en|being used for copyright infringement were warned.In the United States, copyright term has been extended
en|many times over from the original term of 14 years with a single renewal allowance
en|of 14 years, to the current term of the life of the author plus 70
en|years. If the work was produced under corporate authorship it may last 120 years after
en|creation or 95 years after publication, whichever is sooner. Article 50 of the Agreement on
en|Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPs) requires that signatory countries enable courts to remedy
en|copyright infringement with injunctions and the destruction of infringing products, and award damages. Some jurisdictions
en|only allow actual, provable damages, and some, like the U.S., allow for large statutory damage
en|awards intended to deter would-be infringers and allow for compensation in situations where actual damages
en|are difficult to prove. In some jurisdictions, copyright or the right to enforce it can
en|be contractually assigned to a third party which did not have a role in producing
en|the work. When this outsourced litigator appears to have no intention of taking any copyright
en|infringement cases to trial, but rather only takes them just far enough through the legal
en|system to identify and exact settlements from suspected infringers, critics commonly refer to the party
en|as a "copyright troll". Such practices have had mixed results in the U.S. = Criminal
en|law = Punishment of copyright infringement varies case-by-case across countries. Convictions may include jail time
en|and/or severe fines for each instance of copyright infringement. In the United States, willful copyright
en|infringement carries a maximum fine of $150,000 per instance.Article 61 of the Agreement on Trade-Related
en|Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPs) requires that signatory countries establish criminal procedures and penalties
en|in cases of "willful trademark counterfeiting or copyright piracy on a commercial scale". Copyright holders
en|have demanded that states provide criminal sanctions for all types of copyright infringement.The first criminal
en|provision in U.S. copyright law was added in 1897, which established a misdemeanor penalty for
en|"unlawful performances and representations of copyrighted dramatic and musical compositions" if the violation had been
en|"willful and for profit". Criminal copyright infringement requires that the infringer acted "for the purpose
en|of commercial advantage or private financial gain" (17 U.S.C. § 506). To establish criminal liability,
en|the prosecutor must first show the basic elements of copyright infringement: ownership of a valid
en|copyright, and the violation of one or more of the copyright holder's exclusive rights. The
en|government must then establish that defendant willfully infringed or, in other words, possessed the necessary
en|mens rea. Misdemeanor infringement has a very low threshold in terms of number of copies
en|and the value of the infringed works. The ACTA trade agreement, signed in May 2011
en|by the United States, Japan, and the EU, requires that its parties add criminal penalties,
en|including incarceration and fines, for copyright and trademark infringement, and obligated the parties to actively
en|police for infringement.United States v. LaMacchia 871 F.Supp. 535 (1994) was a case decided by
en|the United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts which ruled that, under the
en|copyright and cybercrime laws effective at the time, committing copyright infringement for non-commercial motives could
en|not be prosecuted under criminal copyright law. The ruling gave rise to what became known
en|as the "LaMacchia Loophole", wherein criminal charges of fraud or copyright infringement would be dismissed
en|under current legal standards, so long as there was no profit motive involved.The United States
en|No Electronic Theft Act (NET Act), a federal law passed in 1997, in response to
en|LaMacchia, provides for criminal prosecution of individuals who engage in copyright infringement under certain circumstances,
en|even when there is no monetary profit or commercial benefit from the infringement. Maximum penalties
en|can be five years in prison and up to $250,000 in fines. The NET Act
en|also raised statutory damages by 50%. The court's ruling explicitly drew attention to the shortcomings
en|of current law that allowed people to facilitate mass copyright infringement while being immune to
en|prosecution under the Copyright Act. Proposed laws such as the Stop Online Piracy Act broaden
en|the definition of "willful infringement", and introduce felony charges for unauthorized media streaming. These bills
en|are aimed towards defeating websites that carry or contain links to infringing content, but have
en|raised concerns about domestic abuse and internet censorship. = Noncommercial file sharing = Legality of
en|downloading To an extent, copyright law in some countries permits downloading copyright-protected content for personal,
en|noncommercial use. Examples include Canada and European Union (EU) member states like Poland.The personal copying
en|exemption in the copyright law of EU member states stems from the Information Society Directive
en|of 2001, which is generally devised to allow EU members to enact laws sanctioning making
en|copies without authorization, as long as they are for personal, noncommercial use. The Directive was
en|not intended to legitimize file-sharing, but rather the common practice of space shifting copyright-protected content
en|from a legally purchased CD (for example) to certain kinds of devices and media, provided
en|rights holders are compensated and no copy protection measures are circumvented. Rights-holder compensation takes various
en|forms, depending on the country, but is generally either a levy on "recording" devices and
en|media, or a tax on the content itself. In some countries, such as Canada, the
en|applicability of such laws to copying onto general-purpose storage devices like computer hard drives, portable
en|media players, and phones, for which no levies are collected, has been the subject of
en|debate and further efforts to reform copyright law. In some countries, the personal copying exemption
en|explicitly requires that the content being copied be obtained legitimately – i.e., from authorized sources,
en|not file-sharing networks. In April 2014, the Court of Justice of the European Union ruled
en|that "national legislation which makes no distinction between private copies made from lawful sources and
en|those made from counterfeited or pirated sources cannot be tolerated." Legality of uploading Although downloading
en|or other private copying is sometimes permitted, public distribution – by uploading or otherwise offering
en|to share copyright-protected content – remains illegal in most, if not all, countries. For example,
en|in Canada, even though it was once legal to download any copyrighted file as long
en|as it was for noncommercial use, it was still illegal to distribute the copyrighted files
en|(e.g. by uploading them to a P2P network). Relaxed penalties Some countries, like Canada and
en|Germany, have limited the penalties for non-commercial copyright infringement. For example, Germany has passed a
en|bill to limit the fine for individuals accused of sharing movies and series to €800–900.
en|Canada's Copyright Modernization Act claims that statutory damages for non-commercial copyright infringement are capped at
en|C$5,000 but this only applies to copies that have been made without the breaking of
en|any "digital lock." However, this only applies to "bootleg distribution" and not non-commercial use. =
en|DMCA and anti-circumvention laws = Title I of the U.S. DMCA, the WIPO Copyright and
en|Performances and Phonograms Treaties Implementation Act has provisions that prevent persons from "circumvent[ing] a technological
en|measure that effectively controls access to a work". Thus if a distributor of copyrighted works
en|has some kind of software, dongle or password access device installed in instances of the
en|work, any attempt to bypass such a copy protection scheme may be actionable – though
en|the US Copyright Office is currently reviewing anticircumvention rulemaking under DMCA – anti-circumvention exemptions that
en|have been in place under the DMCA include those in software designed to filter websites
en|that are generally seen to be inefficient (child safety and public library website filtering software)
en|and the circumvention of copy protection mechanisms that have malfunctioned, have caused the instance of
en|the work to become inoperable or which are no longer supported by their manufacturers. According
en|to Abby House Media Inc. v. Apple Inc., it is legal to point users to
en|DRM-stripping software and inform them how to use it because of lack of evidence that
en|DRM stripping leads to copyright infringement. = Online intermediary liability = Whether Internet intermediaries are
en|liable for copyright infringement by their users is a subject of debate and court cases
en|in a number of countries. Definition of intermediary Internet intermediaries were formerly understood to be
en|internet service providers (ISPs). However, questions of liability have also emerged in relation to other
en|Internet infrastructure intermediaries, including Internet backbone providers, cable companies and mobile communications providers.In addition, intermediaries
en|are now also generally understood to include Internet portals, software and games providers, those providing
en|virtual information such as interactive forums and comment facilities with or without a moderation system,
en|aggregators of various kinds, such as news aggregators, universities, libraries and archives, web search engines,
en|chat rooms, web blogs, mailing lists, and any website which provides access to third party
en|content through, for example, hyperlinks, a crucial element of the World Wide Web. Litigation and
en|legislation concerning intermediaries Early court cases focused on the liability of Internet service providers (ISPs)
en|for hosting, transmitting or publishing user-supplied content that could be actioned under civil or criminal
en|law, such as libel or pornography. As different content was considered in different legal systems,
en|and in the absence of common definitions for "ISPs", "bulletin boards" or "online publishers", early
en|law on online intermediaries' liability varied widely from country to country.The debate has shifted away
en|from questions about liability for specific content, including that which may infringe copyright, towards whether
en|online intermediaries should be generally responsible for content accessible through their services or infrastructure.The U.S.
en|Digital Millennium Copyright Act (1998) and the European E-Commerce Directive (2000) provide online intermediaries with
en|limited statutory immunity from liability for copyright infringement. Online intermediaries hosting content that infringes copyright
en|are not liable, so long as they do not know about it and take actions
en|once the infringing content is brought to their attention. In U.S. law this is characterized
en|as "safe harbor" provisions. Under European law, the governing principles for Internet Service Providers are
en|"mere conduit", meaning that they are neutral 'pipes' with no knowledge of what they are
en|carrying; and 'no obligation to monitor' meaning that they cannot be given a general mandate
en|by governments to monitor content. These two principles are a barrier for certain forms of
en|online copyright enforcement and they were the reason behind an attempt to amend the European
en|Telecoms Package in 2009 to support new measures against copyright infringement. Peer-to-peer issues Peer-to-peer file
en|sharing intermediaries have been denied access to safe harbor provisions in relation to copyright infringement.
en|Legal action against such intermediaries, such as Napster, are generally brought in relation to principles
en|of secondary liability for copyright infringement, such as contributory liability and vicarious liability. These types
en|of intermediaries do not host or transmit infringing content, themselves, but may be regarded in
en|some courts as encouraging, enabling or facilitating infringement by users. These intermediaries may include the
en|author, publishers and marketers of peer-to-peer networking software, and the websites that allow users to
en|download such software. In the case of the BitTorrent protocol, intermediaries may include the torrent
en|tracker and any websites or search engines which facilitate access to torrent files. Torrent files
en|do not contain copyrighted content, but they may make reference to files that do, and
en|they may point to trackers which coordinate the sharing of those files. Some torrent indexing
en|and search sites, such as The Pirate Bay, now encourage the use of magnet links,
en|instead of direct links to torrent files, creating another layer of indirection; using such links,
en|torrent files are obtained from other peers, rather than from a particular website. Since the
en|late 1990s, copyright holders have taken legal actions against a number of peer-to-peer intermediaries, such
en|as pir, Grokster, eMule, SoulSeek, BitTorrent and Limewire, and case law on the liability of
en|Internet service providers (ISPs) in relation to copyright infringement has emerged primarily in relation to
en|these cases.Nevertheless, whether and to what degree any of these types of intermediaries have secondary
en|liability is the subject of ongoing litigation. The decentralised structure of peer-to-peer networks, in particular,
en|does not sit easily with existing laws on online intermediaries' liability. The BitTorrent protocol established
en|an entirely decentralised network architecture in order to distribute large files effectively. Recent developments in
en|peer-to-peer technology towards more complex network configurations are said to have been driven by a
en|desire to avoid liability as intermediaries under existing laws. Limitations Copyright law does not grant
en|authors and publishers absolute control over the use of their work. Only certain types of
en|works and kinds of uses are protected; only unauthorized uses of protected works can be
en|said to be infringing. = Non-infringing uses = Article 10 of the Berne Convention mandates
en|that national laws provide for limitations to copyright, so that copyright protection does not extend
en|to certain kinds of uses that fall under what the treaty calls "fair practice", including
en|but not limited to minimal quotations used in journalism and education. The laws implementing these
en|limitations and exceptions for uses that would otherwise be infringing broadly fall into the categories
en|of either fair use or fair dealing. In common law systems, these fair practice statutes
en|typically enshrine principles underlying many earlier judicial precedents, and are considered essential to freedom of
en|speech.Another example is the practice of compulsory licensing, which is where the law forbids copyright
en|owners from denying a license for certain uses of certain kinds of works, such as
en|compilations and live performances of music. Compulsory licensing laws generally say that for certain uses
en|of certain works, no infringement occurs as long as a royalty, at a rate determined
en|by law rather than private negotiation, is paid to the copyright owner or representative copyright
en|collective. Some fair dealing laws, such as Canada's, include similar royalty requirements.In Europe, the copyright
en|infringement case Public Relations Consultants Association Ltd v Newspaper Licensing Agency Ltd had two prongs;
en|one concerned whether a news aggregator service infringed the copyright of the news generators; the
en|other concerned whether the temporary web cache created by the web browser of a consumer
en|of the aggregator's service, also infringed the copyright of the news generators. The first prong
en|was decided in favor of the news generators; in June 2014 the second prong was
en|decided by the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU), which ruled that the
en|temporary web cache of consumers of the aggregator did not infringe the copyright of the
en|news generators. = Non-infringing types of works = In order to qualify for protection, a
en|work must be an expression with a degree of originality, and it must be in
en|a fixed medium, such as written down on paper or recorded digitally. The idea itself
en|is not protected. That is, a copy of someone else's original idea is not infringing
en|unless it copies that person's unique, tangible expression of the idea. Some of these limitations,
en|especially regarding what qualifies as original, are embodied only in case law (judicial precedent), rather
en|than in statutes. In the U.S., for example, copyright case law contains a substantial similarity
en|requirement to determine whether the work was copied. Likewise, courts may require computer software to
en|pass an Abstraction-Filtration-Comparison test (AFC Test) to determine if it is too abstract to qualify
en|for protection, or too dissimilar to an original work to be considered infringing. Software-related case
en|law has also clarified that the amount of R&D, effort and expense put into a
en|work's creation does not affect copyright protection.Evaluation of alleged copyright infringement in a court of
en|law may be substantial; the time and costs required to apply these tests vary based
en|on the size and complexity of the copyrighted material. Furthermore, there is no standard or
en|universally accepted test; some courts have rejected the AFC Test, for example, in favor of
en|narrower criteria. Preventive measures The BSA outlined four strategies that governments can adopt to reduce
en|software piracy rates in its 2011 piracy study results: "Increase public education and raise awareness
en|about software piracy and IP rights in cooperation with industry and law enforcement." "Modernize protections
en|for software and other copyrighted materials to keep pace with new innovations such as cloud
en|computing and the proliferation of networked mobile devices." "Strengthen enforcement of IP laws with dedicated
en|resources, including specialized enforcement units, training for law enforcement and judiciary officials, improved cross-border cooperation
en|among law enforcement agencies, and fulfillment of obligations under the World Trade Organization's Agreement on
en|Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPS)." "Lead by example by using only fully licensed
en|software, implementing software asset management (SAM) programs, and promoting the use of legal software in
en|state-owned enterprises, and among all contractors and suppliers." = Legal = Corporations and legislatures take
en|different types of preventive measures to deter copyright infringement, with much of the focus since
en|the early 1990s being on preventing or reducing digital methods of infringement. Strategies include education,
en|civil and criminal legislation, and international agreements, as well as publicizing anti-piracy litigation successes and
en|imposing forms of digital media copy protection, such as controversial DRM technology and anti-circumvention laws,
en|which limit the amount of control consumers have over the use of products and content
en|they have purchased. Legislatures have reduced infringement by narrowing the scope of what is considered
en|infringing. Aside from upholding international copyright treaty obligations to provide general limitations and exceptions, nations
en|have enacted compulsory licensing laws applying specifically to digital works and uses. For example, in
en|the U.S., the DMCA, an implementation of the 1996 WIPO Copyright Treaty, considers digital transmissions
en|of audio recordings to be licensed as long as a designated copyright collective's royalty and
en|reporting requirements are met. The DMCA also provides safe harbor for digital service providers whose
en|users are suspected of copyright infringement, thus reducing the likelihood that the providers themselves will
en|be considered directly infringing.Some copyright owners voluntarily reduce the scope of what is considered infringement
en|by employing relatively permissive, "open" licensing strategies: rather than privately negotiating license terms with individual
en|users who must first seek out the copyright owner and ask for permission, the copyright
en|owner publishes and distributes the work with a prepared license that anyone can use, as
en|long as they adhere to certain conditions. This has the effect of reducing infringement –
en|and the burden on courts – by simply permitting certain types of uses under terms
en|that the copyright owner considers reasonable. Examples include free software licenses, like the GNU General
en|Public License (GPL), and the Creative Commons licenses, which are predominantly applied to visual and
en|literary works. = Protected distribution = To maximize revenue, pre-COVID-19 film distribution typically began with
en|movie theaters (theatrical window), on average approximately 16 and a half weeks, before the release
en|to Blu-ray and DVD (entering its video window). During the theatrical window, digital versions of
en|films are often transported in data storage devices by couriers rather than by data transmission.
en|The data can be encrypted, with the key being made to work only at specific
en|times in order to prevent leakage between screens. = Watermarking = Coded Anti-Piracy marks can
en|be added to films to identify the source of illegal copies and shut them down.
en|In 2006 a notable example of using Coded Anti-Piracy marks resulted in a man being
en|arrested for uploading a screener's copy of the movie Flushed Away. Some photocopiers use Machine
en|Identification Code dots for similar purposes. The EURion constellation on banknotes is used to prevent
en|copying to make counterfeit currency. Economic impact of copyright infringement Organizations disagree on the scope
en|and magnitude of copyright infringement's free rider economic effects and public support for the copyright
en|regime. The European Commission funded a study to analyze "the extent to which unauthorised online
en|consumption of copyrighted materials (music, audiovisual, books and video games) displaces sales of online and
en|offline legal content", across Germany, the United Kingdom, Spain, France, Poland and Sweden; the public
en|funding behind the study provided a necessary basis for its neutrality. 30,000 users, including minors
en|between 14 and 17 years, were surveyed among September and October 2014. While a negative
en|impact was found for the film industry, videogame sales were positively affected by illegal consumption,
en|possibly due to "the industry being successful in converting illegal users to paying users" and
en|employing player-oriented strategies (for example, by providing additional bonus levels or items in the gameplay
en|for a fee); finally, no evidence was found for any claims of sales displacement in
en|the other market sectors. According to the European Digital Rights association, the study may have
en|been censored: specifically, as of 2018, the European Commission has not published the results, except
en|in the part where the film industry was found to be adversely affected by illegal
en|content consumption. Access to the study was requested and obtained by Member of the European
en|Parliament Felix Reda.In relation to computer software, the Business Software Alliance (BSA) claimed in its
en|2011 piracy study: "Public opinion continues to support intellectual property (IP) rights: Seven PC users
en|in 10 support paying innovators to promote more technological advances."Following consultation with experts on copyright
en|infringement, the United States Government Accountability Office (GAO) clarified in 2010 that "estimating the economic
en|impact of IP [intellectual property] infringements is extremely difficult, and assumptions must be used due
en|to the absence of data", while "it is difficult, if not impossible, to quantify the
en|net effect of counterfeiting and piracy on the economy as a whole."The U.S. GAO's 2010
en|findings regarding the great difficulty of accurately gauging the economic impact of copyright infringement was
en|reinforced within the same report by the body's research into three commonly cited estimates that
en|had previously been provided to U.S. agencies. The GAO report explained that the sources –
en|a Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) estimate, a Customs and Border Protection (CBP) press release
en|and a Motor and Equipment Manufacturers Association estimate – "cannot be substantiated or traced back
en|to an underlying data source or methodology."Deaner explained the importance of rewarding the "investment risk"
en|taken by motion picture studios in 2014: Usually movies are hot because a distributor has
en|spent hundreds of thousands of dollars promoting the product in print and TV and other
en|forms of advertising. The major Hollywood studios spend millions on this process with marketing costs
en|rivaling the costs of production. They are attempting then to monetise through returns that can
en|justify the investment in both the costs of promotion and production. = Motion picture industry
en|estimates = In 2008, the Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA) reported that its six
en|major member companies lost US$6.1 billion to piracy. A 2009 Los Angeles Daily News article
en|then cited a loss figure of "roughly $20 billion a year" for Hollywood studios. According
en|to a 2013 article in The Wall Street Journal, industry estimates in the United States
en|range between $6.1B to $18.5B per year.In an early May 2014 article in The Guardian,
en|an annual loss figure of US$20.5 billion was cited for the movie industry. The article's
en|basis is the results of a University of Portsmouth study that only involved Finnish participants,
en|aged between seven and 84. The researchers, who worked with 6,000 participants, stated: "Movie pirates
en|are also more likely to cut down their piracy if they feel they are harming
en|the industry compared with people who illegally download music".However, a study conducted on data from
en|sixteen countries between 2005 and 2013, many of which had enacted anti-piracy measures to increase
en|box office revenues of movies, found no significant increases in any markets attributable to policy
en|interventions, which calls into doubt the claimed negative economic effects of digital piracy on the
en|film industry. = Software industry estimates = Psion Software claimed in 1983 that software piracy
en|cost it £2.9 million a year, 30% of its revenue. Will Wright said that Raid
en|on Bungeling Bay sold 20,000 copies for the Commodore 64 in the US, but 800,000
en|cartridges for the Nintendo Famicom with a comparable installed base in Japan, "because it's a
en|cartridge system [so] there's virtually no piracy".According to a 2007 BSA and International Data Corporation
en|(IDC) study, the five countries with the highest rates of software piracy were: 1. Armenia
en|(93%); 2. Bangladesh (92%); 3. Azerbaijan (92%); 4. Moldova (92%); and 5. Zimbabwe (91%). According
en|to the study's results, the five countries with the lowest piracy rates were: 1. the
en|U.S. (20%); 2. Luxembourg (21%); 3. New Zealand (22%); 4. Japan (23%); and 5. Austria
en|(25%). The 2007 report showed that the Asia-Pacific region was associated with the highest amount
en|of loss, in terms of U.S. dollars, with $14,090,000, followed by the European Union, with
en|a loss of $12,383,000; the lowest amount of U.S. dollars was lost in the Middle
en|East/Africa region, where $2,446,000 was documented.In its 2011 report, conducted in partnership with IDC and
en|Ipsos Public Affairs, the BSA stated: "Over half of the world's personal computer users –
en|57 percent – admit to pirating software." The ninth annual "BSA Global Software Piracy Study"
en|claims that the "commercial value of this shadow market of pirated software" was worth US$63.4
en|billion in 2011, with the highest commercial value of pirated PC software existent in the
en|U.S. during that time period (US$9,773,000). According to the 2011 study, Zimbabwe was the nation
en|with the highest piracy rate, at 92%, while the lowest piracy rate was present in
en|the U.S., at 19%.The GAO noted in 2010 that the BSA's research up until that
en|year defined "piracy as the difference between total installed software and legitimate software sold, and
en|its scope involved only packaged physical software." = Music industry estimates = In 2007, the
en|Institute for Policy Innovation (IPI) reported that music piracy took $12.5 billion from the U.S.
en|economy. According to the study, musicians and those involved in the recording industry are not
en|the only ones who experience losses attributed to music piracy. Retailers have lost over a
en|billion dollars, while piracy has resulted in 46,000 fewer production-level jobs and almost 25,000 retail
en|jobs. The U.S. government was also reported to suffer from music piracy, losing $422 million
en|in tax revenue.A 2007 study in the Journal of Political Economy found that the effect
en|of music downloads on legal music sales was "statistically indistinguishable from zero".A report from 2013,
en|released by the European Commission Joint Research Centre suggests that illegal music downloads have almost
en|no effect on the number of legal music downloads. The study analyzed the behavior of
en|16,000 European music consumers and found that although music piracy negatively affects offline music sales,
en|illegal music downloads had a positive effect on legal music purchases. Without illegal downloading, legal
en|purchases were about two percent lower.The study has received criticism, particularly from the International Federation
en|of the Phonographic Industry, which believes the study is flawed and misleading. One argument against
en|the research is that many music consumers only download music illegally. The IFPI also points
en|out that music piracy affects not only online music sales but also multiple facets of
en|the music industry, which is not addressed in the study. = Media industry estimates =
en|In a March 2019 article, The New York Times reported that the Qatar-based beIN Media
en|Group suffered "billions of dollars" of losses, following the unilateral cancellation of an exclusive contract
en|it shared with the Asian Football Confederation (AFC) for the past 10 years. The decision
en|by the AFC to invalidate its license for broadcasting rights to air games in Saudi
en|Arabia came after the kingdom was accused of leading a piracy operation through its television
en|broadcaster, beoutQ, misappropriating sports content owned by beIN Sports since 2017, worth billions of dollars.In
en|January 2020, the European Commission released a report on protection and enforcement of intellectual property
en|rights in third countries. The report named as many as 13 countries, including Argentina, Brazil,
en|China, Ecuador, India, Indonesia, and Saudi Arabia, the last being included for the first time.
en|The report said piracy is "causing considerable harm to EU businesses" and high economic losses
en|have occurred in Argentina, China, Ecuador and India. It also informed Saudi Arabia has not
en|"taken sufficient steps to stop the infringement" caused via BeoutQ, like other countries have, to
en|minimize the extent of financial and economic loss. = Criticism of industry estimates = Some
en|claims made by industry representatives have been criticized as overestimating the monetary loss caused by
en|copyright infringement. In one example, the RIAA claimed damages against LimeWire totaling $75 trillion –
en|more than the global GDP – with the judge overseeing the case ruling that such
en|claims were "absurd". The $75 trillion figure had been obtained by counting each song downloaded
en|as an infringement of copyright. After the conclusion of the case, LimeWire agreed to pay
en|$105 million to RIAA.In another decision, US District Court Judge James P. Jones found that
en|the "RIAA's request problematically assumes that every illegal download resulted in a lost sale", indicating
en|profit/loss estimates were likely extremely off. Critics of industry estimates argue that those who use
en|peer-to-peer sharing services, or practice "piracy" are actually more likely to pay for music. A
en|Jupiter Research study in 2000 found that "Napster users were 45 percent more likely to
en|have increased their music purchasing habits than online music fans who don't use the software
en|were." This indicated that users of peer-to-peer sharing did not hurt the profits of the
en|music industry, but in fact may have increased it. Professor Aram Sinnreich, in his book
en|The Piracy Crusade, states that the connection between declining music sales and the creation of
en|peer to peer file sharing sites such as Napster is tenuous, based on correlation rather
en|than causation. He argues that the industry at the time was undergoing artificial expansion, what
en|he describes as a "'perfect bubble'—a confluence of economic, political, and technological forces that drove
en|the aggregate value of music sales to unprecedented heights at the end of the twentieth
en|century". Sinnreich cites multiple causes for the economic bubble, including the CD format replacement cycle;
en|the shift from music specialty stores to wholesale suppliers of music and 'minimum advertised pricing';
en|and the economic expansion of 1991–2001. He believes that with the introduction of new digital
en|technologies, the bubble burst, and the industry suffered as a result. = Economic impact of
en|infringement in emerging markets = The 2011 Business Software Alliance Piracy Study Standard estimated the
en|total commercial value of illegally copied software to be at $59 billion in 2010, with
en|emerging markets accounting for $31.9 billion, over half of the total. Furthermore, mature markets for
en|the first time received fewer PC shipments than emerging economies in 2010. In addition with
