en|In the field of international relations, a sphere of influence is a spatial region or
en|concept division over which a state or organization has a level of cultural, economic, military
en|or political exclusivity.While there may be a formal alliance or other treaty obligations between the
en|influenced and influencer, such formal arrangements are not necessary and the influence can often be
en|more of an example of soft power. Similarly, a formal alliance does not necessarily mean
en|that one country lies within another's sphere of influence. High levels of exclusivity have historically
en|been associated with higher levels of conflict.In more extreme cases, a country within the "sphere
en|of influence" of another may become a subsidiary of that state and serve in effect
en|as a satellite state or de facto colony. This was the case with the Soviet
en|Union and its Eastern Bloc after World War II. The system of spheres of influence
en|by which powerful nations intervene in the affairs of others continues to the present. It
en|is often analyzed in terms of superpowers, great powers, and/or middle powers.Sometimes portions of a
en|single country can fall into two distinct spheres of influence. In the 19th century, the
en|buffer states of Iran and Thailand, lying between the empires of Britain, France and Russia,
en|were divided between the spheres of influence of those three international powers. Likewise, after World
en|War II, Germany was divided into four occupation zones, three of which later consolidated into
en|West Germany and the remaining one became East Germany, the former a member of NATO
en|and the latter a member of the Warsaw Pact. The term is also used to
en|describe non-political situations, e.g., a shopping mall is said to have a 'sphere of influence'
en|that designates the geographical area where it dominates the retail trade. Historical remnants Many powerful
en|states in past centuries had subordinate tributary states, whose native dynasty acknowledged the suzerainty of
en|the great power.Many areas of the world are joined by a cultural influence inherited from
en|a previous sphere of influence, even if they are no longer under political control. Examples
en|include Anglosphere, Arab World, Persosphere, Eurosphere, Francophonie, Françafrique, Germanosphere, Indosphere, Hispanidad, Latin Europe/Latin America, Lusophonie,
en|Turkosphere, Sinosphere, Slavisphere, Malay world, Post-Soviet States and many others. Early United States (1820s) Alexander
en|Hamilton, first U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, aimed for the United States to establish a
en|sphere of influence in North America. Hamilton, writing in the Federalist Papers, harboured ambitions for
en|the US to rise to world power status and gain the strength to expel European
en|powers from the Americas, taking on the mantle of regional dominance among American nations, although
en|most of the New World were European colonies during that period.This doctrine, dubbed the 'Monroe
en|Doctrine', was formalized under President James Monroe, who asserted that the New World was to
en|be established as a Sphere of influence, removed from European encroachment. As the U.S. emerged
en|as a world power, few nations dared to trespass on this sphere. (A notable exception
en|occurred with the Soviet Union and the Cuban Missile Crisis.) As of 2018, Secretary of
en|State Rex Tillerson continued to refer to the Monroe Doctrine to tout the United States
en|as the region's preferred trade partner over other nations such as China. New Imperialism era
en|(late 1800s – early 1900s) For Siam (Thailand), Britain and France signed an agreement in
en|1904 whereby the British recognised a French sphere of influence to the east of the
en|River Menam's (Chao Phraya River) basin; in turn, the French recognised British influence over the
en|territory to the west of the Menam basin and west of the Gulf of Thailand.
en|Both parties disclaimed any idea of annexing Siamese territory.In the Anglo-Russian Convention of 1907, Britain
en|and Russia divided Persia (Iran) into spheres of influence, with the Russians gaining recognition for
en|influence over most of northern Iran, and Britain establishing a zone in the Southeast. =
en|China = In China, during the mid 19th and 20th centuries (known in China as
en|the "century of humiliation"), Great Britain, France, Germany, Russia, and Japan held special powers over
en|large swaths of Chinese territory based on securing "nonalienation commitments" for their "spheres of interest";
en|only the United States was unable to participate due to their involvement in the Spanish–American
en|War. These spheres of influence were acquired by forcing the Qing government to sign "unequal
en|treaties" and long-term leases.In early 1895, the French laid claim to a sphere in Southwest
en|China. By December 1897, German Kaiser Wilhelm II declared his intent to seize territory in
en|China, precipitating the scramble to demarcate zones of influence in China. The Germans acquired, in
en|Shandong province, exclusive control over developmental loans, mining, and railway ownership, while Russia gained a
en|sphere over all territory north of the Great Wall, in addition to the previous tax
en|exemption for trade in Mongolia and Xinjiang, economic powers similar to Germany's over Fengtian, Jilin,
en|and Heilongjiang provinces. France gained a sphere over Yunnan, as well as most of Guangxi
en|and Guangdong provinces; Japan over Fujian province; and the British over the whole Yangtze River
en|valley (defined as all provinces adjoining the Yangtze river as well as Henan and Zhejiang
en|provinces), parts of Guangdong and Guangxi provinces, and part of Tibet. Only Italy's request for
en|Zhejiang province was declined by the Chinese government. These do not include the lease and
en|concession territories where the foreign powers had full authority. The Russian government militarily occupied their
en|zone, imposed their law and schools, seized mining and logging privileges, settled their citizens, and
en|even established their municipal administration on several cities, the latter without Chinese consent.The powers (and
en|the United States) might have their own courts, post offices, commercial institutions, railroads, and gunboats
en|in what was on paper Chinese territory. However, the foreign powers and their control in
en|some cases could have been exaggerated; the local government persistently restricted further encroachment. The system
en|ended after the Second World War. On September 6, 1899, U.S. Secretary of State John
en|Hay sent notes to the major powers (France, Germany, Britain, Italy, Japan, and Russia), asking
en|them to declare formally that they would uphold Chinese territorial and administrative integrity and would
en|not interfere with the free use of the treaty ports within their spheres of influence
en|in China, as the United States felt threatened by other powers' much larger spheres of
en|influence in China and worried that it might lose access to the Chinese market should
en|the country be officially partitioned. Although treaties made after 1900 refer to this "Open Door
en|Policy", competition among the various powers for special concessions within China for railroad rights, mining
en|rights, loans, foreign trade ports, and so forth, continued unabated, with the US itself contradicting
en|the policy by agreeing to recognise the Japanese sphere in the Lansing-Ishii Agreement.In 1910, the
en|great powers, Britain, France, Germany, United States, and later, Russia and Japan, ignored the Open
en|Door Policy to form a banking consortium, consisting of national banking groups backed by respective
en|governments, through which all foreign loans to China were monopolised, granting the powers political influence
en|over China and reducing economic competition between foreigners. This organisation controlled the majority of Chinese
en|tax revenue in a "trust", utilising a small portion to bolster the rule of Chinese
en|warlord Yuan Shikai to great effect. The renewed consortium of UK, France, Japan and the
en|U.S. in 1920 effectively vetoed all developmental loans to China, exerting control over the Chinese
en|government by aiming to control all railroads, ports and highways in China. The Consortium helped
en|to contain the political and financial conflict between parties and states over the loans, while
en|imposing foreign control on China's finances during the period of revolutionary upheaval, which the Consortium
en|also helped to precipitate. World War II (1939–1945) = Empire of Japan = For another
en|example, during the height of its existence in World War II, the Japanese Empire had
en|quite a large sphere of influence. The Japanese government directly governed events in Korea, Vietnam,
en|Taiwan, and parts of Mainland China. The "Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere" could thus be
en|quite easily drawn on a map of the Pacific Ocean as a large "bubble" surrounding
en|the islands of Japan and the Asian and Pacific nations it controlled. = Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact
en|= According to a secret protocol attached to the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact of 1939 (revealed only
en|after Germany's defeat in 1945), Northern and Eastern Europe were divided into Nazi and Soviet
en|spheres of influence: In the north, Finland, Estonia, and Latvia were assigned to the Soviet
en|sphere. Poland was to be partitioned in the event of its "political rearrangement"—the areas east
en|of the Narev, Vistula, and San Rivers going to the Soviet Union, while Germany would
en|occupy the west. Lithuania, adjacent to East Prussia, would be in the German sphere of
en|influence, although a second secret protocol agreed in September 1939 assigned Lithuania to the USSR.Another
en|clause of the treaty stipulated that Bessarabia, then part of Romania, would join the Moldovan
en|ASSR and become the Moldovan SSR under the control of Moscow. The Soviet invasion of
en|Bukovina on 28 June 1940 violated the Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact, as it went beyond the Soviet
en|sphere of influence as agreed with the Axis. The USSR continued to deny the existence
en|of the Pact's protocols until after the dissolution of the Soviet Union when the Russian
en|government fully acknowledged the existence and authenticity of the secret protocols. = End of World
en|War II = From 1941 and the German attack on the Soviet Union, the Allied
en|Coalition operated on the unwritten assumption that the Western Powers and the Soviet Union had
en|each its own sphere of influence. The presumption of the US-British and Soviet unrestricted rights
en|in their respective spheres began to cause difficulties as the Nazi-controlled territory shrank and the
en|allied powers successively liberated other states.The wartime spheres lacked a practical definition and it had
en|never been determined if a dominant allied power was entitled to unilateral decisions only in
en|the area of military activity, or could also force its will regarding political, social and
en|economic future of other states. This overly informal system backfired during the late stages of
en|the war and afterward, when it turned out that the Soviets and the Western Allies
en|had very different ideas concerning the administration and future development of the liberated regions and
en|of Germany itself. Cold War (1947–1991) During the Cold War, the Soviet sphere of influence
en|was said to include: the Baltic states, Central Europe, some countries in Eastern Europe, Cuba,
en|Laos, Vietnam, North Korea, and—until the Sino-Soviet split and Tito–Stalin split—the People's Republic of China
en|and the People's Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, among other countries at various times. Meanwhile, United
en|States was considered to have a sphere of influence over Western Europe, Oceania, Japan, and
en|South Korea, among other places.However, the level of control exerted in these spheres varied and
en|was not absolute. For instance, France and the United Kingdom were able to act independently
en|to invade (with Israel) the Suez Canal (they were later forced to withdraw by joint
en|U.S. and Soviet pressure). Later, France was also able to withdraw from the military arm
en|of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO). Cuba, as another example, often took positions that
en|put it at odds with its Soviet ally, including momentary alliances with China, economic reorganizations,
en|and providing support for insurgencies in Africa and the Americas without prior approval from the
en|Soviet Union.With the end of the Cold War, the Eastern Bloc fell apart, effectively ending
en|the Soviet sphere of influence. Then in 1991, the Soviet Union ceased to exist, replaced
en|by the Russian Federation and several other ex-Soviet Republics who became independent states. Contemporary Russia
en|(1990s–present) Following the fall of the Soviet Union, the countries of the Commonwealth of Independent
en|States that became independent in 1991, were portrayed as part of the Russian Federation's 'sphere
en|of influence', according to a statement by Boris Yeltsin, dated September 1994.According to Ulrich Speck,
en|writing for Carnegie Europe, "After the breakup of the Soviet Union, the West's focus was
en|on Russia. Western nations implicitly treated the post-Soviet countries (besides the Baltic states) as Russia's
en|sphere of influence."In 1997, NATO and Russia signed the Founding Act on Mutual Relations, Cooperation
en|and Security, stating the "aim of creating in Europe a common space of security and
en|stability, without dividing lines or spheres of influence limiting the sovereignty of any state."On August
en|31, 2008, Russian president Dmitri Medvedev stated five principles of foreign policy, including the claim
en|of a privileged sphere of influence that comprised "the border region, but not only". In
en|2009, Russia asserted that the European Union desires a sphere of influence and that the
en|Eastern Partnership is "an attempt to extend" it. In March that year, Swedish Foreign Minister
en|Carl Bildt stated that the "Eastern Partnership is not about spheres of influence. The difference
en|is that these countries themselves opted to join." Following the 2008 Russo-Georgian War, Václav Havel
en|and other former central and eastern European leaders signed an open letter stating that Russia
en|had "violated the core principles of the Helsinki Final Act, the Charter of Paris ...
en|all in the name of defending a sphere of influence on its borders." In April
en|2014, NATO stated that, contrary to the Founding Act,Russia now appears to be attempting to
en|recreate a sphere of influence by seizing a part of Ukraine, maintaining large numbers of
en|forces on its borders, and demanding, as Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov recently stated, that
en|"Ukraine cannot be part of any bloc."Criticising Russia in November 2014, German Chancellor Angela Merkel
en|said that "old thinking about spheres of influence, which runs roughshod over international law" put
en|the "entire European peace order into question." In January 2017, British Prime Minister Theresa May
en|said, "We should not jeopardise the freedoms that President Reagan and Mrs Thatcher brought to
en|Eastern Europe by accepting President Putin's claim that it is now in his sphere of
en|influence." Contemporary United States (1991–present) Corporations In corporate terms, the sphere of influence of a
en|business, organization, or group can show its power and influence in the decisions of other
en|businesses/organizations/groups. The influence shows in several ways, such as in size, frequency of visits, etc.
en|In most cases, a company described as "bigger" has a larger sphere of influence. For
en|example, the software company Microsoft has a large sphere of influence in the market of
en|operating systems; any entity wishing to sell a software product may weigh up compatibility with
en|Microsoft's products as part of a marketing plan. In another example, retailers wishing to make
en|the most profits must ensure they open their stores in the correct location. This is
en|also true for shopping centers that, to reap the most profits, must be able to
en|attract customers to their vicinity.There is no defined scale measuring such spheres of influence. However,
en|one can evaluate the spheres of influence of two shopping centers by seeing how far
en|people are prepared to travel to each shopping center, how much time they spend in
en|its vicinity, how often they visit, the order of goods available, etc.Corporations have significant influence
en|on the regulations and regulators that monitor them. During the Gilded Age in the United
en|States, corruption was rampant as business leaders spent significant amounts of money ensuring that government
en|did not regulate their activities. Wall Street spent a record $2 billion trying to influence
en|the 2016 United States elections. List of spheres of influence America's Backyard — areas of
en|United States' influence in the American continent Anglosphere — English-speaking world Arabsphere — Arabic-speaking world
en|Sinosphere — historically Chinese-influenced cultures Russian world — Russian-speaking world Eurosphere — area with European
en|Union influence Francosphere — French-speaking world Germanosphere — German-speaking world Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere
en|— imperial influence of the Japanese Empire Hispanosphere — Spanish-speaking world Indosphere — area with
en|Indian linguistic and cultural influence (Greater India) Islamosphere — the Muslim world Persophere — historically
en|Iran-influenced cultures Slavisphere — Slavic influence Soviet sphere of influence — imperial influence of the
en|Soviet Union = Other examples = For historical and current examples of significant battles over
