en|The history of Europe is traditionally divided into four time periods: prehistoric Europe (prior to
en|about 800 BC), classical antiquity (800 BC to AD 500), the Middle Ages (AD 500
en|to AD 1500), and the modern era (since AD 1500). The first early European modern
en|humans appear in the fossil record about 48,000 years ago, during the Paleolithic Era. Settled
en|agriculture marked the Neolithic Era, which spread slowly across Europe from southeast to the north
en|and west. The later Neolithic period saw the introduction of early metallurgy and the use
en|of copper-based tools and weapons, and the building of megalithic structures, as exemplified by Stonehenge.
en|During the Indo-European migrations, Europe saw migrations from the east and southeast. The period known
en|as classical antiquity began with the emergence of the city-states of ancient Greece. Later, the
en|Roman Empire came to dominate the entire Mediterranean basin. The Migration Period of the Germanic
en|people began in the late 4th century AD and made gradual incursions into various parts
en|of the Roman Empire. The Fall of the Western Roman Empire in AD 476 traditionally
en|marks the start of the Middle Ages. While the Eastern Roman Empire would continue for
en|another 1000 years, the former lands of the Western Empire would be fragmented into a
en|number of different states. At the same time, the early Slavs began to become established
en|as a distinct group in the central and eastern parts of Europe. The first great
en|empire of the Middle Ages was the Frankish Empire of Charlemagne, while the Islamic conquest
en|of Iberia established Al-Andalus. The Viking Age saw a second great migration of Norse peoples.
en|Attempts to retake the Levant from the Muslim states that occupied it made the High
en|Middle Ages the age of The Crusades, while the political system of feudalism came to
en|its height. The Late Middle Ages were marked by large population declines, as Europe was
en|threatened by the Bubonic Plague, as well as invasions by the Mongol peoples from the
en|Eurasian Steppe. At the end of the Middle Ages, there was a transitional period, known
en|as the Renaissance. Early Modern Europe is usually dated to the end of the 15th
en|century. Technological changes such as gunpowder and the printing press changed how warfare was conducted
en|and how knowledge was preserved and disseminated. The Protestant Reformation saw the fragmentation of religious
en|thought, leading to religious wars. The Age of Exploration led to colonization, and the exploitation
en|of the people and resources of colonies brought resources and wealth to Europe. After 1800,
en|the Industrial Revolution brought capital accumulation and rapid urbanization to Western Europe, while several countries
en|transitioned away from absolutist rule to parliamentary regimes. The Age of Revolutions saw long-established political
en|systems upset and turned over. In the 20th century, World War I led to a
en|remaking of the map of Europe as the large Empires were broken up into nation-states.
en|Lingering political issues would lead to World War II, during which Nazi Germany perpetrated the
en|Holocaust. After World War II, during the Cold War, most of Europe became divided by
en|the Iron Curtain in two military blocs: NATO and the Warsaw Pact. The post-war period
en|saw decolonization as Western European colonial empires were dismantled. The post-war period also featured the
en|gradual development of the European integration process, which led to the creation of the European
en|Union; this extended to Eastern European countries after the Fall of the Berlin Wall. The
en|21st century saw the European debt crisis, the withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the
en|European Union and the Russian invasion of Ukraine. Prehistory of Europe = Paleolithic = Homo
en|erectus migrated from Africa to Europe before the emergence of modern humans. Homo erectus georgicus,
en|which lived roughly 1.8 million years ago in Georgia, is the earliest hominid to have
en|been discovered in Europe. The earliest appearance of anatomically modern people in Europe has been
en|dated to 45,000 BC, referred to as the Early European modern humans. Some locally developed
en|transitional cultures (Uluzzian in Italy and Greece, Altmühlian in Germany, Szeletian in Central Europe and
en|Châtelperronian in the southwest) use clearly Upper Palaeolithic technologies at very early dates. Nevertheless, the
en|definitive advance of these technologies is made by the Aurignacian culture, originating in the Levant
en|(Ahmarian) and Hungary (first full Aurignacian). By 35,000 BC, the Aurignacian culture and its technology
en|had extended through most of Europe. The last Neanderthals seem to have been forced to
en|retreat to the southern half of the Iberian Peninsula. Around 29,000 BC a new technology/culture
en|appeared in the western region of Europe: the Gravettian. This technology/culture has been theorised to
en|have come with migrations of people from the Balkans (see Kozarnika). Around 16,000 BC, Europe
en|witnessed the appearance of a new culture, known as Magdalenian, possibly rooted in the old
en|Gravettian. This culture soon superseded the Solutrean area and the Gravettian of mainly France, Spain,
en|Germany, Italy, Poland, Portugal and Ukraine. The Hamburg culture prevailed in Northern Europe in the
en|14th and the 13th millennium BC as the Creswellian (also termed the British Late Magdalenian)
en|did shortly after in the British Isles. Around 12,500 BC, the Würm glaciation ended. Magdalenian
en|culture persisted until c. 10,000 BC, when it quickly evolved into two microlithist cultures: Azilian
en|(Federmesser), in Spain and southern France, and then Sauveterrian, in southern France and Tardenoisian in
en|Central Europe, while in Northern Europe the Lyngby complex succeeded the Hamburg culture with the
en|influence of the Federmesser group as well. = Neolithic and Copper Age = Evidence of
en|permanent settlement dates from the 8th millennium BC in the Balkans. The Neolithic reached Central
en|Europe in the 6th millennium BC and parts of Northern Europe in the 5th and
en|4th millenniums BC. The modern indigenous populations of Europe are largely descended from three distinct
en|lineages: Mesolithic hunter-gatherers, a derivative of the Cro-Magnon population, Early European Farmers who migrated from
en|Anatolia during the Neolithic Revolution, and Yamnaya pastoralists who expanded into Europe in the context
en|of the Indo-European expansion. The Indo-European migrations started in Southeast Europe at around c. 4200
en|BC. through the areas around the Black sea and the Balkan peninsula. In the next
en|3000 years the Indo-European languages expanded through Europe. Around this time, in the 5th millennium
en|BC the Varna culture evolved. In 4700 – 4200 BC, the Solnitsata town, believed to
en|be the oldest prehistoric town in Europe, flourished.The Tumulus and the following Urnfield culture of
en|central europe were part of the origin of the Roman and Greek cultures. Ancient Europe
en|= Bronze Age = The first well-known literate civilization in Europe was the Minoan civilization
en|that arose on the island of Crete and flourished from approximately the 27th century BC
en|to the 15th century BC.The Minoans were replaced by the Mycenaean civilization which flourished during
en|the period roughly between 1600 BC, when Helladic culture in mainland Greece was transformed under
en|influences from Minoan Crete, and 1100 BC. The major Mycenaean cities were Mycenae and Tiryns
en|in Argolis, Pylos in Messenia, Athens in Attica, Thebes and Orchomenus in Boeotia, and Iolkos
en|in Thessaly. In Crete, the Mycenaeans occupied Knossos. Mycenaean settlement sites also appeared in Epirus,
en|Macedonia, on islands in the Aegean Sea, on the coast of Asia Minor, the Levant,
en|Cyprus and Italy. Mycenaean artefacts have been found well outside the limits of the Mycenean
en|world. Quite unlike the Minoans, whose society benefited from trade, the Mycenaeans advanced through conquest.
en|Mycenaean civilization was dominated by a warrior aristocracy. Around 1400 BC, the Mycenaeans extended their
en|control to Crete, the centre of the Minoan civilization, and adopted a form of the
en|Minoan script (called Linear A) to write their early form of Greek in Linear B.
en|The Mycenaean civilization perished with the collapse of Bronze-Age civilization on the eastern shores of
en|the Mediterranean Sea. The collapse is commonly attributed to the Dorian invasion, although other theories
en|describing natural disasters and climate change have been advanced as well. Whatever the causes, the
en|Mycenaean civilization had definitely disappeared after LH III C, when the sites of Mycenae and
en|Tiryns were again destroyed and lost their importance. This end, during the last years of
en|the 12th century BC, occurred after a slow decline of the Mycenaean civilization, which lasted
en|many years before dying out. The beginning of the 11th century BC opened a new
en|context, that of the protogeometric, the beginning of the geometric period, the Greek Dark Ages
en|of traditional historiography. The Bronze Age collapse may be seen in the context of a
en|technological history that saw the slow spread of ironworking technology from present-day Bulgaria and Romania
en|in the 13th and the 12th centuries BC. = Classical Antiquity = = Ancient Greece
en|= The Hellenic civilisation was a collection of city-states or poleis with different governments and
en|cultures that achieved notable developments in government, philosophy, science, mathematics, politics, sports, theatre and music.
en|The most powerful city-states were Athens, Sparta, Thebes, Corinth, and Syracuse. Athens was a powerful
en|Hellenic city-state and governed itself with an early form of direct democracy invented by Cleisthenes;
en|the citizens of Athens voted on legislation and executive bills themselves. Athens was the home
en|of Socrates, Plato, and the Platonic Academy. The Hellenic city-states established colonies on the shores
en|of the Black Sea and the Mediterranean Sea (Asian Minor, Sicily, and Southern Italy in
en|Magna Graecia). By the late 6th century BC, the Greek city states in Asia Minor
en|had been incorporated into the Persian Empire, while the latter had made territorial gains in
en|the Balkans (such as Macedon, Thrace, Paeonia, etc.) and Eastern Europe proper as well. In
en|the course of the 5th century BC, some of the Greek city states attempted to
en|overthrow Persian rule in the Ionian Revolt, which failed. This sparked the first Persian invasion
en|of mainland Greece. At some point during the ensuing Greco-Persian Wars, namely during the Second
en|Persian invasion of Greece, and precisely after the Battle of Thermopylae and the Battle of
en|Artemisium, almost all of Greece to the north of the Isthmus of Corinth had been
en|overrun by the Persians, but the Greek city states reached a decisive victory at the
en|Battle of Plataea. With the end of the Greco-Persian wars, the Persians were eventually forced
en|to withdraw from their territories in Europe. The Greco-Persian Wars and the victory of the
en|Greek city states directly influenced the entire further course of European history and would set
en|its further tone. Some Greek city-states formed the Delian League to continue fighting Persia, but
en|Athens' position as leader of this league led Sparta to form the rival Peloponnesian League.
en|The Peloponnesian Wars ensued, and the Peloponnesian League was victorious. Subsequently, discontent with Spartan hegemony
en|led to the Corinthian War and the defeat of Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra.
en|At the same time at the north ruled the Thracian Odrysian Kingdom between the 5th
en|century BC and the 1st century AD. Hellenic infighting left Greek city states vulnerable, and
en|Philip II of Macedon united the Greek city states under his control. The son of
en|Philip II, known as Alexander the Great, invaded neighboring Persia, toppled and incorporated its domains,
en|as well as invading Egypt and going as far off as India, increasing contact with
en|people and cultures in these regions that marked the beginning of the Hellenistic period. After
en|the death of Alexander the Great, his empire split into multiple kingdoms ruled by his
en|generals, the Diadochi. The Diadochi fought against each other in a series of conflicts called
en|the Wars of the Diadochi. In the beginning of the 2nd century BC, only three
en|major kingdoms remained: the Ptolemaic Egypt, the Seleucid Empire and Macedonia. These kingdoms spread Greek
en|culture to regions as far away as Bactria. = Ancient Rome = Much of Greek
en|learning was assimilated by the nascent Roman state as it expanded outward from Italy, taking
en|advantage of its enemies' inability to unite: the only challenge to Roman ascent came from
en|the Phoenician colony of Carthage, and its defeats in the three Punic Wars marked the
en|start of Roman hegemony. First governed by kings, then as a senatorial republic (the Roman
en|Republic), Rome finally became an empire at the end of the 1st century BC, under
en|Augustus and his authoritarian successors. The Roman Empire had its centre in the Mediterranean, controlling
en|all the countries on its shores; the northern border was marked by the Rhine and
en|Danube rivers. Under the emperor Trajan (2nd century AD) the empire reached its maximum expansion,
en|controlling approximately 5,900,000 km2 (2,300,000 sq mi) of land surface, including Italia, Gallia, Dalmatia, Aquitania,
en|Britannia, Baetica, Hispania, Thrace, Macedonia, Greece, Moesia, Dacia, Pannonia, Egypt, Asia Minor, Cappadocia, Armenia, Caucasus,
en|North Africa, Levant and parts of Mesopotamia. Pax Romana, a period of peace, civilisation and
en|an efficient centralised government in the subject territories ended in the 3rd century, when a
en|series of civil wars undermined Rome's economic and social strength. In the 4th century, the
en|emperors Diocletian and Constantine were able to slow down the process of decline by splitting
en|the empire into a Western part with a capital in Rome and an Eastern part
en|with the capital in Byzantium, or Constantinople (now Istanbul). Constantinople is generally considered to be
en|the center of "Eastern Orthodox civilization". Whereas Diocletian severely persecuted Christianity, Constantine declared an official
en|end to state-sponsored persecution of Christians in 313 with the Edict of Milan, thus setting
en|the stage for the Church to become the state church of the Roman Empire in
en|about 380. The Roman Empire had been repeatedly attacked by invading armies from Northern Europe
en|and in 476, Rome finally fell. Romulus Augustus, the last emperor of the Western Roman
en|Empire, surrendered to the Germanic King Odoacer. = Late Antiquity and Migration Period = When
en|Emperor Constantine had reconquered Rome under the banner of the cross in 312, he soon
en|afterwards issued the Edict of Milan in 313 (preceded by the Edict of Serdica in
en|311), declaring the legality of Christianity in the Roman Empire. In addition, Constantine officially shifted
en|the capital of the Roman Empire from Rome to the Greek town of Byzantium, which
en|he renamed Nova Roma – it was later named Constantinople ("City of Constantine"). Theodosius I,
en|who had made Christianity the official religion of the Roman Empire, would be the last
en|emperor to preside over a united Roman Empire, until his death in 395. The empire
en|was split into two halves: the Western Roman Empire centred in Ravenna, and the Eastern
en|Roman Empire (later to be referred to as the Byzantine Empire) centred in Constantinople. The
en|Roman Empire was repeatedly attacked by Hunnic, Germanic, Slavic and other "barbarian" tribes (see: Migration
en|Period), and in 476 finally the Western part fell to the Heruli chieftain Odoacer. Roman
en|authority in the Western part of the empire had collapsed, and a power vacuum left
en|in the wake of this collapse; the central organization, institutions, laws and power of Rome
en|had broken down, resulting in many areas being open to invasion by migrating tribes. Over
en|time, feudalism and manorialism arose, providing for division of land and labour, as well as
en|a broad if uneven hierarchy of law and protection. These localised hierarchies were based on
en|the bond of common people to the land on which they worked, and to a
en|lord, who would provide and administer both local law to settle disputes among the peasants,
en|as well as protection from outside invaders. The western provinces soon were to be dominated
en|by three great powers: first, the Franks (Merovingian dynasty) in Francia 481–843 AD, which covered
en|much of present France and Germany; second, the Visigothic kingdom 418–711 AD in the Iberian
en|Peninsula (modern Spain); and third, the Ostrogothic kingdom 493–553 AD in Italy and parts of
en|the western Balkans. The Ostrogoths were later replaced by the Kingdom of the Lombards 568–774
en|AD. Although these powers covered large territories, they did not have the great resources and
en|bureaucracy of the Roman empire to control regions and localities; more power and responsibilities were
en|left to local lords. On the other hand, it also meant more freedom, particularly in
en|more remote areas. In Italy, Theodoric the Great began the cultural romanisation of the new
en|world he had constructed. He made Ravenna a centre of Romano-Greek culture of art and
en|his court fostered a flowering of literature and philosophy in Latin. In Iberia, King Chindasuinth
en|created the Visigothic Code. In the Eastern part the dominant state was the remaining Eastern
en|Roman Empire. In the feudal system, new princes and kings arose, the most powerful of
en|which was arguably the Frankish ruler Charlemagne. In 800, Charlemagne, reinforced by his massive territorial
en|conquests, was crowned Emperor of the Romans by Pope Leo III, solidifying his power in
en|western Europe. Charlemagne's reign marked the beginning of a new Germanic Roman Empire in the
en|west, the Holy Roman Empire. Outside his borders, new forces were gathering. The Kievan Rus'
en|were marking out their territory, a Great Moravia was growing, while the Angles and the
en|Saxons were securing their borders. For the duration of the 6th century, the Eastern Roman
en|Empire was embroiled in a series of deadly conflicts, first with the Persian Sassanid Empire
en|(see Roman–Persian Wars), followed by the onslaught of the arising Islamic Caliphate (Rashidun and Umayyad).
en|By 650, the provinces of Egypt, Palestine and Syria were lost to the Muslim forces,
en|followed by Hispania and southern Italy in the 7th and 8th centuries (see Muslim conquests).
en|The Arab invasion from the east was stopped after the intervention of the Bulgarian Empire
en|(see Han Tervel). Post-classical Europe The Middle Ages are commonly dated from the fall of
en|the Western Roman Empire (or by some scholars, before that) in the 5th century to
en|the beginning of the early modern period in the 16th century marked by the rise
en|of nation states, the division of Western Christianity in the Reformation, the rise of humanism
en|in the Italian Renaissance, and the beginnings of European overseas expansion which allowed for the
en|Columbian Exchange. = Byzantium = Many consider Emperor Constantine I (reigned 306–337) to be the
en|first "Byzantine emperor". It was he who moved the imperial capital in 324 from Nicomedia
en|to Byzantium, which re-founded as Constantinople, or Nova Roma ("New Rome"). The city of Rome
en|itself had not served as the capital since the reign of Diocletian (284–305). Some date
en|the beginnings of the Empire to the reign of Theodosius I (379–395) and Christianity's official
en|supplanting of the pagan Roman religion, or following his death in 395, when the empire
en|was split into two parts, with capitals in Rome and Constantinople. Others place it yet
en|later in 476, when Romulus Augustulus, traditionally considered the last western emperor, was deposed, thus
en|leaving sole imperial authority with the emperor in the Greek East. Others point to the
en|reorganisation of the empire in the time of Heraclius (c. 620) when Latin titles and
en|usages were officially replaced with Greek versions. In any case, the changeover was gradual and
en|by 330, when Constantine inaugurated his new capital, the process of hellenization and increasing Christianisation
en|was already under way. The Empire is generally considered to have ended after the fall
en|of Constantinople to the Ottoman Turks in 1453. The Plague of Justinian was a pandemic
en|that afflicted the Byzantine Empire, including its capital Constantinople, in the years 541–542. It is
en|estimated that the Plague of Justinian killed as many as 100 million people. It caused
en|Europe's population to drop by around 50% between 541 and 700. It also may have
en|contributed to the success of the Muslim conquests. During most of its existence, the Byzantine
en|Empire was one of the most powerful economic, cultural, and military forces in Europe, and
en|Constantinople was one of the largest and wealthiest cities in Europe. = Early Middle Ages
en|= The Early Middle Ages span roughly five centuries from 500 to 1000. In the
en|East and Southeast of Europe new dominant states formed: the Avar Khaganate (567–after 822), Old
en|Great Bulgaria (632–668), the Khazar Khaganate (c. 650–969) and Danube Bulgaria (founded by Asparuh in
en|680) were constantly rivaling the hegemony of the Byzantine Empire. From the 7th century Byzantine
en|history was greatly affected by the rise of Islam and the Caliphates. Muslim Arabs first
en|invaded historically Roman territory under Abū Bakr, first Caliph of the Rashidun Caliphate, who entered
en|Roman Syria and Roman Mesopotamia. As the Byzantines and neighboring Sasanids were severely weakened by
en|the time, amongst the most important reason(s) being the protracted, centuries-lasting and frequent Byzantine–Sasanian wars,
en|which included the climactic Byzantine–Sasanian War of 602–628, under Umar, the second Caliph, the Muslims
en|entirely toppled the Sasanid Persian Empire, and decisively conquered Syria and Mesopotamia, as well as
en|Roman Palestine, Roman Egypt, and parts of Asia Minor and Roman North Africa. In the
en|mid 7th century AD, following the Muslim conquest of Persia, Islam penetrated into the Caucasus
en|region, of which parts would later permanently become part of Russia. This trend, which included
en|the conquests by the invading Muslim forces and by that the spread of Islam as
en|well continued under Umar's successors and under the Umayyad Caliphate, which conquered the rest of
en|Mediterranean North Africa and most of the Iberian Peninsula. Over the next centuries Muslim forces
en|were able to take further European territory, including Cyprus, Malta, Crete, and Sicily and parts
en|of southern Italy.The Muslim conquest of Hispania began when the Moors invaded the Christian Visigothic
en|kingdom of Hispania in 711, under the Berber general Tariq ibn Ziyad. They landed at
en|Gibraltar on 30 April and worked their way northward. Tariq's forces were joined the next
en|year by those of his Arab superior, Musa ibn Nusair. During the eight-year campaign most
en|of the Iberian Peninsula was brought under Muslim rule – save for small areas in
en|the northwest (Asturias) and largely Basque regions in the Pyrenees. In 711, Visigothic Hispania was
en|weakened because it was immersed in a serious internal crisis caused by a war of
en|succession to the throne. The Muslims took advantage of the crisis within the Hispano-Visigothic society
en|to carry out their conquests. This territory, under the Arab name Al-Andalus, became part of
en|the expanding Umayyad empire. The second siege of Constantinople (717) ended unsuccessfully after the intervention
en|of Tervel of Bulgaria and weakened the Umayyad dynasty and reduced their prestige. In 722
en|Don Pelayo formed an army of 300 Astur soldiers, to confront Munuza's Muslim troops. In
en|the battle of Covadonga, the Astures defeated the Arab-Moors, who decided to retire. The Christian
en|victory marked the beginning of the Reconquista and the establishment of the Kingdom of Asturias,
en|whose first sovereign was Don Pelayo. The conquerors intended to continue their expansion in Europe
en|and move northeast across the Pyrenees, but were defeated by the Frankish leader Charles Martel
en|at the Battle of Poitiers in 732. The Umayyads were overthrown in 750 by the
en|'Abbāsids, and, in 756, the Umayyads established an independent emirate in the Iberian Peninsula. Feudal
en|Christendom The Holy Roman Empire emerged around 800, as Charlemagne, King of the Franks and
en|part of the Carolingian dynasty, was crowned by the pope as emperor. His empire based
en|in modern France, the Low Countries and Germany expanded into modern Hungary, Italy, Bohemia, Lower
en|Saxony and Spain. He and his father received substantial help from an alliance with the
en|Pope, who wanted help against the Lombards. His death marked the beginning of the end
en|of the dynasty, which collapsed entirely by 888. The fragmentation of power led to semi-autonomy
en|in the region, and has been defined as a critical starting point for the formation
en|of states in Europe.To the east, Bulgaria was established in 681 and became the first
en|Slavic country. The powerful Bulgarian Empire was the main rival of Byzantium for control of
en|the Balkans for centuries and from the 9th century became the cultural centre of Slavic
en|Europe. The Empire created the Cyrillic script during the 9th century AD, at the Preslav
en|Literary School, and experienced the Golden Age of Bulgarian cultural prosperity during the reign of
en|emperor Simeon I the Great (893–927). Two states, Great Moravia and Kievan Rus', emerged among
en|the Slavic peoples respectively in the 9th century. In the late 9th and 10th centuries,
en|northern and western Europe felt the burgeoning power and influence of the Vikings who raided,
en|traded, conquered and settled swiftly and efficiently with their advanced seagoing vessels such as the
en|longships. The Vikings had left a cultural influence on the Anglo-Saxons and Franks as well
en|as the Scots. The Hungarians pillaged mainland Europe, the Pechenegs raided Bulgaria, Rus States and
en|the Arab states. In the 10th century independent kingdoms were established in Central Europe including
en|Poland and the newly settled Kingdom of Hungary. The Kingdom of Croatia also appeared in
en|the Balkans. The subsequent period, ending around 1000, saw the further growth of feudalism, which
en|weakened the Holy Roman Empire. In eastern Europe, Volga Bulgaria became an Islamic state in
en|921, after Almış I converted to Islam under the missionary efforts of Ahmad ibn Fadlan.Slavery
en|in the early medieval period had mostly died out in western Europe by about the
en|year 1000 AD, replaced by serfdom. It lingered longer in England and in peripheral areas
en|linked to the Muslim world, where slavery continued to flourish. Church rules suppressed slavery of
en|Christians. Most historians argue the transition was quite abrupt around 1000, but some see a
en|gradual transition from about 300 to 1000. = High Middle Ages = In 1054, the
en|East–West Schism occurred between the two remaining Christian seats in Rome and Constantinople (modern Istanbul).
en|The High Middle Ages of the 11th, 12th, and 13th centuries show a rapidly increasing
en|population of Europe, which caused great social and political change from the preceding era. By
en|1250, the robust population increase greatly benefited the economy, reaching levels it would not see
en|again in some areas until the 19th century.From about the year 1000 onwards, Western Europe
en|saw the last of the barbarian invasions and became more politically organized. The Vikings had
en|settled in Britain, Ireland, France and elsewhere, whilst Norse Christian kingdoms were developing in their
en|Scandinavian homelands. The Magyars had ceased their expansion in the 10th century, and by the
en|year 1000, the Roman Catholic Apostolic Kingdom of Hungary was recognised in central Europe. With
en|the brief exception of the Mongol invasions, major barbarian incursions ceased. Bulgarian sovereignty was re-established
en|with the anti-Byzantine uprising of the Bulgarians and Vlachs in 1185. The crusaders invaded the
en|Byzantine empire, captured Constantinople in 1204 and established their Latin Empire. Kaloyan of Bulgaria defeated
en|Baldwin I, Latin Emperor of Constantinople, in the Battle of Adrianople on 14 April 1205.
en|The reign of Ivan Asen II of Bulgaria led to maximum territorial expansion and that
en|of Ivan Alexander of Bulgaria to a Second Golden Age of Bulgarian culture. The Byzantine
en|Empire was fully re-established in 1261. In the 11th century, populations north of the Alps
en|began to settle new lands. Vast forests and marshes of Europe were cleared and cultivated.
en|At the same time settlements moved beyond the traditional boundaries of the Frankish Empire to
en|new frontiers in Europe, beyond the Elbe river, tripling the size of Germany in the
en|process. Crusaders founded European colonies in the Levant, the majority of the Iberian Peninsula was
en|conquered from the Muslims, and the Normans colonised southern Italy, all part of the major
en|population increase and resettlement pattern. The High Middle Ages produced many different forms of intellectual,
en|spiritual and artistic works. The most famous are the great cathedrals as expressions of Gothic
en|architecture, which evolved from Romanesque architecture. This age saw the rise of modern nation-states in
en|Western Europe and the ascent of the famous Italian city-states, such as Florence and Venice.
en|The influential popes of the Catholic Church called volunteer armies from across Europe to a
en|series of Crusades against the Seljuq Turks, who occupied the Holy Land. The rediscovery of
en|the works of Aristotle led Thomas Aquinas and other thinkers to develop the philosophy of
en|Scholasticism. Holy wars After the East–West Schism, Western Christianity was adopted by the newly created
en|kingdoms of Central Europe: Poland, Hungary and Bohemia. The Roman Catholic Church developed as a
en|major power, leading to conflicts between the Pope and emperor. The geographic reach of the
en|Roman Catholic Church expanded enormously due to the conversions of pagan kings (Scandinavia, Lithuania, Poland,
en|Hungary), the Christian Reconquista of Al-Andalus, and the crusades. Most of Europe was Roman Catholic
en|in the 15th century. Early signs of the rebirth of civilization in western Europe began
en|to appear in the 11th century as trade started again in Italy, leading to the
en|economic and cultural growth of independent city-states such as Venice and Florence; at the same
en|time, nation-states began to take form in places such as France, England, Spain, and Portugal,
en|although the process of their formation (usually marked by rivalry between the monarchy, the aristocratic
en|feudal lords and the church) actually took several centuries. These new nation-states began writing in
en|their own cultural vernaculars, instead of the traditional Latin. Notable figures of this movement would
en|include Dante Alighieri and Christine de Pizan. The Holy Roman Empire, essentially based in Germany
en|and Italy, further fragmented into a myriad of feudal principalities or small city states, whose
en|subjection to the emperor was only formal. The 14th century, when the Mongol Empire came
en|to power, is often called the Age of the Mongols. Mongol armies expanded westward under
en|the command of Batu Khan. Their western conquests included almost all of Kievan Rus' (save
en|Novgorod, which became a vassal), and the Kipchak-Cuman Confederation. Bulgaria, Hungary, and Poland managed to
en|remain sovereign states. Mongolian records indicate that Batu Khan was planning a complete conquest of
en|the remaining European powers, beginning with a winter attack on Austria, Italy and Germany, when
en|he was recalled to Mongolia upon the death of Great Khan Ögedei. Most historians believe
en|only his death prevented the complete conquest of Europe. The areas of Eastern Europe and
en|most of Central Asia that were under direct Mongol rule became known as the Golden
en|Horde. Under Uzbeg Khan, Islam became the official religion of the region in the early
en|14th century. The invading Mongols, together with their mostly Turkic subjects, were known as Tatars.
en|In Russia, the Tatars ruled the various states of the Rus' through vassalage for over
en|300 years. In the Northern Europe, Konrad of Masovia gave Chełmno to the Teutonic Knights
en|in 1226 as a base for a Crusade against the Old Prussians and Grand Duchy
en|of Lithuania. The Livonian Brothers of the Sword were defeated by the Lithuanians, so in
en|1237 Gregory IX merged the remainder of the order into the Teutonic Order as the
en|Livonian Order. By the middle of the century, the Teutonic Knights completed their conquest of
en|the Prussians before converting the Lithuanians in the subsequent decades. The order also came into
en|conflict with the Eastern Orthodox Church of the Pskov and Novgorod Republics. In 1240 the
en|Orthodox Novgorod army defeated the Catholic Swedes in the Battle of the Neva, and, two
en|years later, they defeated the Livonian Order in the Battle on the Ice. The Union
en|of Krewo in 1386, bringing two major changes in the history of the Grand Duchy
en|of Lithuania: conversion to Catholicism and establishment of a dynastic union between the Grand Duchy
en|of Lithuania and the Crown of the Kingdom of Poland marked both the greatest territorial
en|expansion of the Grand Duchy and the defeat of the Teutonic Knights in the Battle
en|of Grunwald in 1410. = Late Middle Ages = The Late Middle Ages spanned around
en|the 14th and late 15th centuries. Around 1300, centuries of European prosperity and growth came
en|to a halt. A series of famines and plagues, such as the Great Famine of
en|1315–1317 and the Black Death, killed people in a matter of days, reducing the population
en|of some areas by half as many survivors fled. Kishlansky reports: The Black Death touched
en|every aspect of life, hastening a process of social, economic, and cultural transformation already underway....
en|Fields were abandoned, workplaces stood idle, international trade was suspended. Traditional bonds of kinship, village,
en|and even religion were broken amid the horrors of death, flight, and failed expectations. "People
en|cared no more for dead men than we care for dead goats," wrote one survivor.Depopulation
en|caused labor to become scarcer; the survivors were better paid and peasants could drop some
en|of the burdens of feudalism. There was also social unrest; France and England experienced serious
en|peasant risings including the Jacquerie and the Peasants' Revolt. The unity of the Catholic Church
en|was shattered by the Great Schism. Collectively these events have been called the Crisis of
en|the Late Middle Ages.Beginning in the 14th century, the Baltic Sea became one of the
en|most important trade routes. The Hanseatic League, an alliance of trading cities, facilitated the absorption
en|of vast areas of Poland, Lithuania, and Livonia into trade with other European countries. This
en|fed the growth of powerful states in this part of Europe including Poland–Lithuania, Hungary, Bohemia,
en|and Muscovy later on. The conventional end of the Middle Ages is usually associated with
en|the fall of the city of Constantinople and of the Byzantine Empire to the Ottoman
en|Turks in 1453. The Turks made the city the capital of their Ottoman Empire, which
en|lasted until 1922 and included Egypt, Syria, and most of the Balkans. The Ottoman wars
en|in Europe marked an essential part of the history of the continent. A key 15th-century
en|development was the advent of the movable type of printing press circa 1439 in Mainz,
en|building upon the impetus provided by the prior introduction of paper from China via the
en|Arabs in the High Middle Ages. The adoption of the technology across the continent at
en|dazzling speed for the remaining part of the 15th century would usher a revolution and
en|by 1500 over 200 cities in Europe had presses that printed between 8 and 20
en|million books. Early modern Europe The Early Modern period spans the centuries between the Middle
en|Ages and the Industrial Revolution, roughly from 1500 to 1800, or from the discovery of
en|the New World in 1492 to the French Revolution in 1789. The period is characterised
en|by the rise in importance of science and increasingly rapid technological progress, secularised civic politics,
en|and the nation state. Capitalist economies began their rise, and the early modern period also
en|saw the rise and dominance of the economic theory of mercantilism. As such, the early
en|modern period represents the decline and eventual disappearance, in much of the European sphere, of
en|feudalism, serfdom and the power of the Catholic Church. The period includes the Renaissance, the
en|Scientific Revolution, the Protestant Reformation, the disastrous Thirty Years' War, the European colonisation of the
en|Americas and the European witch-hunts. = Renaissance = Despite these crises, the 14th century was
en|also a time of great progress within the arts and sciences. A renewed interest in
en|ancient Greek and Roman led to the Italian Renaissance, a cultural movement that profoundly affected
en|European intellectual life in the early modern period. Beginning in Italy, and spreading to the
en|north, west and middle Europe during a cultural lag of some two and a half
en|centuries, its influence affected literature, philosophy, art, politics, science, history, religion, and other aspects of
en|intellectual inquiry. The Humanists saw their repossession of a great past as a Renaissance –
en|a rebirth of civilization itself. Important political precedents were also set in this period. Niccolò
en|Machiavelli's political writing in The Prince influenced later absolutism and realpolitik. Also important were the
en|many patrons who ruled states and used the artistry of the Renaissance as a sign
en|of their power. The Scientific Revolution took place in Europe starting towards the second half
en|of the Renaissance period, with the 1543 Nicolaus Copernicus publication De revolutionibus orbium coelestium (On
en|the Revolutions of the Heavenly Spheres) often cited as its beginning. = Exploration and trade
en|= Toward the end of the period, an era of discovery began. The growth of
en|the Ottoman Empire, culminating in the fall of Constantinople in 1453, cut off trading possibilities
en|with the east. Western Europe was forced to discover new trading routes, as happened with
en|Columbus' travel to the Americas in 1492, and Vasco da Gama's circumnavigation of India and
en|Africa in 1498. The numerous wars did not prevent European states from exploring and conquering
en|wide portions of the world, from Africa to Asia and the newly discovered Americas. In
en|the 15th century, Portugal led the way in geographical exploration along the coast of Africa
en|in search of a maritime route to India, followed by Spain near the close of
en|the 15th century, dividing their exploration of the world according to the Treaty of Tordesillas
en|in 1494. They were the first states to set up colonies in America and European
en|trading posts (factories) along the shores of Africa and Asia, establishing the first direct European
en|diplomatic contacts with Southeast Asian states in 1511, China in 1513 and Japan in 1542.
en|In 1552, Russian tsar Ivan the Terrible conquered two major Tatar khanates, the Khanate of
en|Kazan and the Astrakhan Khanate. The Yermak's voyage of 1580 led to the annexation of
en|the Tatar Siberian Khanate into Russia, and the Russians would soon after conquer the rest
en|of Siberia, steadily expanding to the east and south over the next centuries. Oceanic explorations
en|soon followed by France, England and the Netherlands, who explored the Portuguese and Spanish trade
en|routes into the Pacific Ocean, reaching Australia in 1606 and New Zealand in 1642. =
en|Reformation = With the development of the printing press, new ideas spread throughout Europe and
en|challenged traditional doctrines in science and theology. Simultaneously, the Protestant Reformation under German Martin Luther
en|questioned Papal authority. The most common dating of the Reformation begins in 1517, when Luther
en|published The Ninety-Five Theses, and concludes in 1648 with the Treaty of Westphalia that ended
en|years of European religious wars.During this period corruption in the Catholic Church led to a
en|sharp backlash in the Protestant Reformation. It gained many followers especially among princes and kings
en|seeking a stronger state by ending the influence of the Catholic Church. Figures other than
en|Martin Luther began to emerge as well like John Calvin whose Calvinism had influence in
en|many countries and King Henry VIII of England who broke away from the Catholic Church
en|in England and set up the Anglican Church. These religious divisions brought on a wave
en|of wars inspired and driven by religion but also by the ambitious monarchs in Western
en|Europe who were becoming more centralized and powerful. The Protestant Reformation also led to a
en|strong reform movement in the Catholic Church called the Counter-Reformation, which aimed to reduce corruption
en|as well as to improve and strengthen Catholic dogma. Two important groups in the Catholic
en|Church who emerged from this movement were the Jesuits, who helped keep Spain, Portugal, Poland,
en|and other European countries within the Catholic fold, and the Oratorians of Saint Philip Neri,
en|who ministered to the faithful in Rome, restoring their confidence in the Church of Jesus
en|Christ that subsisted substantially in the Church of Rome. Still, the Catholic Church was somewhat
en|weakened by the Reformation, portions of Europe were no longer under its sway and kings
en|in the remaining Catholic countries began to take control of the church institutions within their
en|kingdoms. Unlike many European countries, the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth and Hungary were more tolerant. While still
en|enforcing the predominance of Catholicism, they continued to allow the large religious minorities to maintain
en|their faiths, traditions and customs. The Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth became divided among Catholics, Protestants, Orthodox, Jews
en|and a small Muslim population. Another development was the idea of 'European superiority'. There was
en|a movement by some such as Montaigne that regarded the non-Europeans as a better, more
en|natural and primitive people. Post services were founded all over Europe, which allowed a humanistic
en|interconnected network of intellectuals across Europe, despite religious divisions. However, the Roman Catholic Church banned
en|many leading scientific works; this led to an intellectual advantage for Protestant countries, where the
en|banning of books was regionally organised. Francis Bacon and other advocates of science tried to
en|create unity in Europe by focusing on the unity in nature.1 In the 15th century,
en|at the end of the Middle Ages, powerful sovereign states were appearing, built by the
en|New Monarchs who were centralising power in France, England, and Spain. On the other hand,
en|the Parliament in the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth grew in power, taking legislative rights from the Polish
en|king. The new state power was contested by parliaments in other countries especially England. New
en|kinds of states emerged which were co-operation agreements among territorial rulers, cities, farmer republics and
en|knights. = Mercantilism and colonial expansion = The Iberian kingdoms were able to dominate colonial
en|activity in the 16th century. The Portuguese forged the first global empire in the 15th
en|and 16th century, whilst during the 16th century and the first half of the 17th
en|century, the crown of Castile (and the overarching Hispanic Monarchy, including Portugal from 1580 to
en|1640) became the most powerful empire in the world. Spanish dominance in America was increasingly
en|challenged by British, French, Dutch and Swedish colonial efforts of the 17th and 18th centuries.
en|New forms of trade and expanding horizons made new forms of government, law and economics
en|necessary. Colonial expansion continued in the following centuries (with some setbacks, such as successful wars
en|of independence in the British American colonies and then later Haiti, Mexico, Argentina, Brazil, and
en|others amid European turmoil of the Napoleonic Wars). Spain had control of a large part
en|of North America, all of Central America and a great part of South America, the
en|Caribbean and the Philippines; Britain took the whole of Australia and New Zealand, most of
en|India, and large parts of Africa and North America; France held parts of Canada and
en|India (nearly all of which was lost to Britain in 1763), Indochina, large parts of
en|Africa and the Caribbean islands; the Netherlands gained the East Indies (now Indonesia) and islands
en|in the Caribbean; Portugal obtained Brazil and several territories in Africa and Asia; and later,
en|powers such as Germany, Belgium, Italy and Russia acquired further colonies.This expansion helped the economy
en|of the countries owning them. Trade flourished, because of the minor stability of the empires.
en|By the late 16th century, American silver accounted for one-fifth of Spain's total budget. The
en|French colony of Saint-Domingue was one of richest European colonies in the 18th century, operating
en|on a plantation economy fueled by slave labor. During the period of French rule, cash
en|crops produced in Saint-Domingue comprised thirty percent of total French trade while its sugar exports
en|represented forty percent of the Atlantic market. = Crisis of the 17th century = The
en|17th century was an era of crisis. Many historians have rejected the idea, while others
en|promote it as an invaluable insight into the warfare, politics, economics, and even art. The
en|Thirty Years' War (1618–1648) focused attention on the massive horrors that wars could bring to
en|entire populations. The 1640s in particular saw more state breakdowns around the world than any
en|previous or subsequent period. The Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, the largest state in Europe, temporarily disappeared. In
en|addition, there were secessions and upheavals in several parts of the Spanish empire, the world's
en|first global empire. In Britain the entire Stuart monarchy (England, Scotland, Ireland, and its North
en|American colonies) rebelled. Political insurgency and a spate of popular revolts seldom equalled shook the
en|foundations of most states in Europe and Asia. More wars took place around the world
en|in the mid-17th century than in almost any other period of recorded history. Across the
en|Northern Hemisphere, the mid-17th century experienced almost unprecedented death rates. = Age of absolutism =
en|The "absolute" rule of powerful monarchs such as Louis XIV (ruled France 1643–1715), Peter the
en|Great (ruled Russia 1682–1725), Maria Theresa (ruled Habsburg lands 1740–1780) and Frederick the Great (ruled
en|Prussia 1740–86), produced powerful centralized states, with strong armies and powerful bureaucracies, all under the
en|control of the king.Throughout the early part of this period, capitalism (through mercantilism) was replacing
en|feudalism as the principal form of economic organisation, at least in the western half of
en|Europe. The expanding colonial frontiers resulted in a Commercial Revolution. The period is noted for
en|the rise of modern science and the application of its findings to technological improvements, which
en|animated the Industrial Revolution after 1750. The Reformation had profound effects on the unity of
en|Europe. Not only were nations divided one from another by their religious orientation, but some
en|states were torn apart internally by religious strife, avidly fostered by their external enemies. France
en|suffered this fate in the 16th century in the series of conflicts known as the
en|French Wars of Religion, which ended in the triumph of the Bourbon Dynasty. England settled
en|down under Elizabeth I to a moderate Anglicanism. Much of modern-day Germany was made up
en|of numerous small sovereign states under the theoretical framework of the Holy Roman Empire, which
en|was further divided along internally drawn sectarian lines. The Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth is notable in this
en|time for its religious indifference and general immunity to European religious strife. Thirty Years' War
en|1618–1648 The Thirty Years' War was fought between 1618 and 1648, across Germany and neighbouring
en|areas, and involved most of the major European powers except England and Russia, involving Catholics
en|versus Protestants for the most part. The major impact of the war was the devastation
en|of entire regions scavenged bare by the foraging armies. Episodes of widespread famine and disease,
en|and the breakup of family life, devastated the population of the German states and, to
en|a lesser extent, the Low Countries, the Crown of Bohemia and northern parts of Italy,
en|while bankrupting many of the regional powers involved. Between one-fourth and one-third of the German
en|population perished from direct military causes or from disease and starvation, as well as postponed
en|births. After the Peace of Westphalia, which ended the war in favour of nations deciding
en|their own religious allegiance, absolutism became the norm of the continent, while parts of Europe
en|experimented with constitutions foreshadowed by the English Civil War and particularly the Glorious Revolution. European
en|military conflict did not cease, but had less disruptive effects on the lives of Europeans.
en|In the advanced northwest, the Enlightenment gave a philosophical underpinning to the new outlook, and
en|the continued spread of literacy, made possible by the printing press, created new secular forces
en|in thought. From the Union of Krewo, central and eastern Europe was dominated by Kingdom
en|of Poland and Grand Duchy of Lithuania. In the 16th and 17th centuries Central and
en|Eastern Europe was an arena of conflict for domination of the continent between Sweden, the
en|Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth (involved in series of wars, like Khmelnytsky uprising, Russo-Polish War, the Deluge, etc.)
en|and the Ottoman Empire. This period saw a gradual decline of these three powers which
en|were eventually replaced by new enlightened absolutist monarchies: Russia, Prussia and Austria (the Habsburg monarchy).
en|By the turn of the 19th century they had become new powers, having divided Poland
en|between themselves, with Sweden and Turkey having experienced substantial territorial losses to Russia and Austria
en|respectively as well as pauperisation. War of the Spanish Succession The War of the Spanish
en|Succession (1701–1715) was a major war with France opposed by a coalition of England, the
en|Netherlands, the Habsburg monarchy, and Prussia. Duke of Marlborough commanded the English and Dutch victory
en|at the Battle of Blenheim in 1704. The main issue was whether France under King
en|Louis XIV would take control of Spain's very extensive possessions and thereby become by far
en|the dominant power, or be forced to share power with other major nations. After initial
en|allied successes, the long war produced a military stalemate and ended with the Treaty of
en|Utrecht, which was based on a balance of power in Europe. Historian Russell Weigley argues
en|that the many wars almost never accomplished more than they cost. British historian G. M.
en|Trevelyan argues: That Treaty [of Utrecht], which ushered in the stable and characteristic period of
en|Eighteenth-Century civilization, marked the end of danger to Europe from the old French monarchy, and
en|it marked a change of no less significance to the world at large – the
en|maritime, commercial and financial supremacy of Great Britain. Prussia Frederick the Great, king of Prussia
en|1740–86, modernized the Prussian army, introduced new tactical and strategic concepts, fought mostly successful wars
en|(Silesian Wars, Seven Years' War) and doubled the size of Prussia. Russia Russia fought numerous
en|wars to achieve rapid expansion toward the east – i.e. Siberia, Far East, south, to
en|the Black Sea, and south-east and to central Asia. Russia boasted a large and powerful
en|army, a very large and complex internal bureaucracy, and a splendid court that rivaled Paris
en|and London. However the government was living far beyond its means and seized Church lands,
en|leaving organized religion in a weak condition. Throughout the 18th century Russia remained "a poor,
en|backward, overwhelmingly agricultural, and illiterate country." = Enlightenment = The Enlightenment was a powerful, widespread
en|cultural movement of intellectuals beginning in late 17th-century Europe emphasizing the power of reason rather
en|than tradition; it was especially favourable to science (especially Isaac Newton's physics) and hostile to
en|religious orthodoxy (especially of the Catholic Church). It sought to analyze and reform society using
en|reason, to challenge ideas grounded in tradition and faith, and to advance knowledge through the
en|scientific method. It promoted scientific thought, skepticism, and intellectual interchange. The Enlightenment was a revolution
en|in human thought. This new way of thinking was that rational thought begins with clearly
en|stated principles, uses correct logic to arrive at conclusions, tests the conclusions against evidence, and
en|then revises the principles in light of the evidence. Enlightenment thinkers opposed superstition. Some Enlightenment
en|thinkers collaborated with Enlightened despots, absolutist rulers who attempted to forcibly impose some of the
en|new ideas about government into practice. The ideas of the Enlightenment exerted significant influence on
en|the culture, politics, and governments of Europe.Originating in the 17th century, it was sparked by
en|philosophers Francis Bacon, Baruch Spinoza, John Locke, Pierre Bayle, Voltaire, Francis Hutcheson, David Hume and
en|physicist Isaac Newton. Ruling princes often endorsed and fostered these figures and even attempted to
en|apply their ideas of government in what was known as enlightened absolutism. The Scientific Revolution
en|is closely tied to the Enlightenment, as its discoveries overturned many traditional concepts and introduced
en|new perspectives on nature and man's place within it. The Enlightenment flourished until about 1790–1800,
en|at which point the Enlightenment, with its emphasis on reason, gave way to Romanticism, which
en|placed a new emphasis on emotion; a Counter-Enlightenment began to increase in prominence. In France,
en|Enlightenment was based in the salons and culminated in the great Encyclopédie (1751–72). These new
en|intellectual strains would spread to urban centres across Europe, notably England, Scotland, the German states,
en|the Netherlands, Poland, Russia, Italy, Austria, and Spain, as well as Britain's American colonies. The
en|political ideals of the Enlightenment influenced the American Declaration of Independence, the United States Bill
en|of Rights, the French Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen, and
en|the Polish–Lithuanian Constitution of 3 May 1791.Norman Davies has argued that Freemasonry was a powerful
en|force on behalf of Liberalism and Enlightenment ideas in Europe, from about 1700 to the
en|20th century. It expanded rapidly during the Age of Enlightenment, reaching practically every country in
en|Europe. The great enemy of Freemasonry was the Roman Catholic Church, so that in countries
en|with a large Catholic element, such as France, Italy, Austria, Spain and Mexico, much of
en|the ferocity of the political battles involve the confrontation between supporters of the Church versus
en|active Masons. 20th-century totalitarian and revolutionary movements, especially the Fascists and Communists, crushed the Freemasons.
en|From revolution to imperialism (1789–1914) The "long 19th century", from 1789 to 1914 saw the
en|drastic social, political and economic changes initiated by the Industrial Revolution, the French Revolution and
en|the Napoleonic Wars. Following the reorganisation of the political map of Europe at the Congress
en|of Vienna in 1815, Europe experienced the rise of Nationalism, the rise of the Russian
en|Empire and the peak of the British Empire, as well as the decline of the
en|Ottoman Empire. Finally, the rise of the German Empire and the Austro-Hungarian Empire initiated the
en|course of events that culminated in the outbreak of the First World War in 1914.
en|= Industrial Revolution = The Industrial Revolution saw major changes in agriculture, manufacturing, and transport
en|impacted Britain and subsequently spread to the United States and Western Europe. Technological advancements, most
en|notably the utilization of the steam engine, were major catalysts in the industrialisation process. It
en|started in England and Scotland in the mid-18th century with the mechanisation of the textile
en|industries, the development of iron-making techniques and the increased use of coal as the main
en|fuel. Trade expansion was enabled by the introduction of canals, improved roads and railways. The
en|introduction of steam power (fuelled primarily by coal) and powered machinery (mainly in textile manufacturing)
en|underpinned the dramatic increases in production capacity. The development of all-metal machine tools in the
en|first two decades of the 19th century facilitated the manufacture of more production machines for
en|manufacturing in other industries. The effects spread throughout Western Europe and North America during the
en|19th century, eventually affecting most of the world. = Era of the French Revolution =
en|Historians R.R. Palmer and Joel Colton argue: In 1789 France fell into revolution, and the
en|world has never since been the same. The French Revolution was by far the most
en|momentous upheaval of the whole revolutionary age. It replaced the "old regime" with "modern society,"
en|and at its extreme phase became very radical, so much so that all later revolutionary
en|movements have looked back to it as a predecessor to themselves.... From the 1760s to
en|1848, the role of France was decisive.The era of the French Revolution and the subsequent
en|Napoleonic wars was a difficult time for monarchs. Tsar Paul I of Russia was assassinated;
en|King Louis XVI of France was executed, as was his queen Marie Antoinette. Furthermore, kings
en|Charles IV of Spain, Ferdinand VII of Spain and Gustav IV Adolf of Sweden were
en|deposed as were ultimately the Emperor Napoleon and all of the relatives he had installed
en|on various European thrones. King Frederick William III of Prussia and Emperor Francis II of
en|Austria barely clung to their thrones. King George III of Great Britain lost the better
en|part of the First British Empire.The American Revolution (1775–1783) was the first successful revolt of
en|a colony against a European power. It rejected aristocracy and established a republican form of
en|government that attracted worldwide attention. The French Revolution (1789–1804) was a product of the same
en|democratic forces in the Atlantic World and had an even greater impact. French historian François
en|Aulard says: From the social point of view, the Revolution consisted in the suppression of
en|what was called the feudal system, in the emancipation of the individual, in greater division
en|of landed property, the abolition of the privileges of noble birth, the establishment of equality,
en|the simplification of life.... The French Revolution differed from other revolutions in being not merely
en|national, for it aimed at benefiting all humanity."French intervention in the American Revolutionary War had
en|nearly bankrupted the state. After repeated failed attempts at financial reform, King Louis XVI had
en|to convene the Estates-General, a representative body of the country made up of three estates:
en|the clergy, the nobility, and the commoners. The third estate, joined by members of the
en|other two, declared itself to be a National Assembly and created, in July, the National
en|Constituent Assembly. At the same time the people of Paris revolted, famously storming the Bastille
en|prison on 14 July 1789. At the time the assembly wanted to create a constitutional
en|monarchy, and over the following two years passed various laws including the Declaration of the
en|Rights of Man and of the Citizen, the abolition of feudalism, and a fundamental change
en|in the relationship between France and Rome. At first the king agreed with these changes
en|and enjoyed reasonable popularity with the people. As anti-royalism increased along with threat of foreign
en|invasion, the king tried to flee and join France's enemies. He was captured and on
en|21 January 1793, having been convicted of treason, he was guillotined. On 20 September 1792
en|the National Convention abolished the monarchy and declared France a republic. Due to the emergency
en|of war, the National Convention created the Committee of Public Safety to act as the
en|country's executive. Under Maximilien de Robespierre, the committee initiated the Reign of Terror, during which
en|up to 40,000 people were executed in Paris, mainly nobles and those convicted by the
en|Revolutionary Tribunal, often on the flimsiest of evidence. Internal tensions at Paris drove the Committee
en|towards increasing assertions of radicalism and increasing suspicions. A few months into this phase, more
en|and more prominent revolutionaries were being sent to the guillotine by Robespierre and his faction,
en|for example Madame Roland and Georges Danton. Elsewhere in the country, counter-revolutionary insurrections were brutally
en|suppressed. The regime was overthrown in the coup of 9 Thermidor (27 July 1794) and
en|Robespierre was executed. The regime which followed ended the Terror and relaxed Robespierre's more extreme
en|policies. = Napoleon = Napoleon Bonaparte was France's most successful general in the Revolutionary wars.
en|In 1799 on 18 Brumaire (9 November) he overthrew the government, replacing it with the
en|Consulate, which he dominated. He gained popularity in France by restoring the Church, keeping taxes
en|low, centralizing power in Paris, and winning glory on the battlefield. In 1804 he crowned
en|himself Emperor. In 1805, Napoleon planned to invade Britain, but a renewed British alliance with
en|Russia and Austria (Third Coalition), forced him to turn his attention towards the continent, while
en|at the same time the French fleet was demolished by the British at the Battle
en|of Trafalgar, ending any plan to invade Britain. On 2 December 1805, Napoleon defeated a
en|numerically superior Austro-Russian army at Austerlitz, forcing Austria's withdrawal from the coalition (see Treaty of
en|Pressburg) and dissolving the Holy Roman Empire. In 1806, a Fourth Coalition was set up.
en|On 14 October Napoleon defeated the Prussians at the Battle of Jena-Auerstedt, marched through Germany
en|and defeated the Russians on 14 June 1807 at Friedland. The Treaties of Tilsit divided
en|Europe between France and Russia and created the Duchy of Warsaw. On 12 June 1812
en|Napoleon invaded Russia with a Grande Armée of nearly 700,000 troops. After the measured victories
en|at Smolensk and Borodino Napoleon occupied Moscow, only to find it burned by the retreating
en|Russian army. He was forced to withdraw. On the march back his army was harassed
en|by Cossacks, and suffered disease and starvation. Only 20,000 of his men survived the campaign.
en|By 1813 the tide had begun to turn from Napoleon. Having been defeated by a
en|seven nation army at the Battle of Leipzig in October 1813, he was forced to
en|abdicate after the Six Days' Campaign and the occupation of Paris. Under the Treaty of
en|Fontainebleau he was exiled to the island of Elba. He returned to France on 1
en|March 1815 (see Hundred Days), raised an army, but was finally defeated by a British
en|and Prussian force at the Battle of Waterloo on 18 June 1815 and exiled to
en|the small British island of Saint Helena. Impact of the French Revolution Roberts finds that
en|the Revolutionary and Napoleonic wars, from 1793 to 1815, caused 4 million deaths (of whom
en|1 million were civilians); 1.4 million were French.Outside France the Revolution had a major impact.
en|Its ideas became widespread. Roberts argues that Napoleon was responsible for key ideas of the
en|modern world, so that, "meritocracy, equality before the law, property rights, religious toleration, modern secular
en|education, sound finances, and so on-were protected, consolidated, codified, and geographically extended by Napoleon during
en|his 16 years of power."Furthermore, the French armies in the 1790s and 1800s directly overthrew
en|feudal remains in much of western Europe. They liberalised property laws, ended seigneurial dues, abolished
en|the guild of merchants and craftsmen to facilitate entrepreneurship, legalised divorce, closed the Jewish ghettos
en|and made Jews equal to everyone else. The Inquisition ended as did the Holy Roman
en|Empire. The power of church courts and religious authority was sharply reduced and equality under
en|the law was proclaimed for all men.France conquered Belgium and turned it into another province
en|of France. It conquered the Netherlands, and made it a client state. It took control
en|of the German areas on the left bank of the Rhine River and set up
en|a puppet Confederation of the Rhine. It conquered Switzerland and most of Italy, setting up
en|a series of puppet states. The result was glory and an infusion of much needed
en|money from the conquered lands. However the enemies of France, led by Britain, formed a
en|Second Coalition in 1799 (with Britain joined by Russia, the Ottoman Empire and Austria). It
en|scored a series of victories that rolled back French successes, and trapped the French Army
en|in Egypt. Napoleon slipped through the British blockade in October 1799, returning to Paris, where
en|he overthrew the government and made himself the ruler.Napoleon conquered most of Italy in the
en|name of the French Revolution in 1797–99. He split up Austria's holdings and set up
en|a series of new republics, complete with new codes of law and abolition of feudal
en|privileges. Napoleon's Cisalpine Republic was centered on Milan; Genoa became a republic; the Roman Republic
en|was formed as well as the small Ligurian Republic around Genoa. The Neapolitan Republic was
en|formed around Naples, but it lasted only five months. He later formed the Kingdom of
en|Italy, with his brother as King. In addition, France turned the Netherlands into the Batavian
en|Republic, and Switzerland into the Helvetic Republic. All these new countries were satellites of France,
en|and had to pay large subsidies to Paris, as well as provide military support for
en|Napoleon's wars. Their political and administrative systems were modernized, the metric system introduced, and trade
en|barriers reduced. Jewish ghettos were abolished. Belgium and Piedmont became integral parts of France. Most
en|of the new nations were abolished and returned to prewar owners in 1814. However, Artz
en|emphasizes the benefits the Italians gained from the French Revolution: For nearly two decades the
en|Italians had excellent codes of law, a fair system of taxation, a better economic situation,
en|and more religious and intellectual toleration than they had known for centuries.... Everywhere old physical,
en|economic, and intellectual barriers had been thrown down and the Italians had begun to be
en|aware of a common nationality.Likewise in Switzerland the long-term impact of the French Revolution has
en|been assessed by Martin: It proclaimed the equality of citizens before the law, equality of
en|languages, freedom of thought and faith; it created a Swiss citizenship, basis of our modern
en|nationality, and the separation of powers, of which the old regime had no conception; it
en|suppressed internal tariffs and other economic restraints; it unified weights and measures, reformed civil and
en|penal law, authorized mixed marriages (between Catholics and Protestants), suppressed torture and improved justice; it
en|developed education and public works.The greatest impact came in France itself. In addition to effects
en|similar to those in Italy and Switzerland, France saw the introduction of the principle of
en|legal equality, and the downgrading of the once powerful and rich Catholic Church. Power became
en|centralized in Paris, with its strong bureaucracy and an army supplied by conscripting all young
en|men. French politics were permanently polarized – new names were given, "left" and "right" for
en|the supporters and opponents of the principles of the Revolution. = Religion = By the
en|19th century, governments increasingly took over traditional religious roles, paying much more attention to efficiency
en|and uniformity than to religiosity. Secular bodies took control of education away from the churches,
en|abolished taxes and tithes for the support of established religions, and excluded bishops from the
en|upper houses. Secular laws increasingly regulated marriage and divorce, and maintaining birth and death registers
en|became the duty of local officials. Although the numerous religious denominations in the United States
en|founded many colleges and universities, that was almost exclusively a state function across Europe. Imperial
en|powers protected Christian missionaries in African and Asian colonies. In France and other largely Catholic
en|nations, anti-clerical political movements tried to reduce the role of the Catholic Church. Likewise briefly
en|in Germany in the 1870s there was a fierce Kulturkampf (culture war) against Catholics, but
en|the Catholics successfully fought back. The Catholic Church concentrated more power in the papacy and
en|fought against secularism and socialism. It sponsored devotional reforms that gained wide support among the
en|churchgoers. = Nations rising = The political development of nationalism and the push for popular
en|sovereignty culminated with the ethnic/national revolutions of Europe. During the 19th century nationalism became one
en|of the most significant political and social forces in history; it is typically listed among
en|the top causes of World War I. Most European states had become constitutional monarchies by
en|1871, and Germany and Italy merged many small city-states to become united nation-states. Germany in
en|particular increasingly dominated the continent in economics and political power. Meanwhile, on a global scale,
en|Great Britain, with its far-flung British Empire, unmatched Royal Navy, and powerful bankers, became the
en|world's first global power. The sun never set on its territories, while an informal empire
en|operated through British financiers, entrepreneurs, traders and engineers who established operations in many countries, and
en|largely dominated Latin America. The British were especially famous for financing and constructing railways around
en|the world.Napoleon's conquests of the German and Italian states around 1800–1806 played a major role
en|in stimulating nationalism and demand for national unity. Germany In the German states east of
en|Prussia Napoleon abolished many of the old or medieval relics, such as dissolving the Holy
en|Roman Empire in 1806. He imposed rational legal systems and his organization of the Confederation
en|of the Rhine in 1806 promoted a feeling of German nationalism. In the 1860s it
en|was Prussian chancellor Otto von Bismarck who achieved German unification in 1870 after the many
en|smaller states followed Prussia's leadership in wars against Denmark, Austria and France. Italy Italian nationalism
en|emerged in the 19th century and was the driving force for Italian unification or the
en|"Risorgimento". It was the political and intellectual movement that consolidated different states of the Italian
en|Peninsula into the single state of the Kingdom of Italy in 1860. The memory of
en|the Risorgimento is central to both Italian nationalism and Italian historiography. Serbia For centuries the
en|Orthodox Christian Serbs were ruled by the Muslim-controlled Ottoman Empire. The success of the Serbian
en|revolution (1804–1817) against Ottoman rule in 1817 marked the foundation of modern Principality of Serbia.
en|It achieved de facto independence in 1867 and finally gained recognition in the Berlin Congress
en|of 1878. The Serbs developed a larger vision for nationalism in Pan-Slavism and with Russian
en|support sought to pull the other Slavs out of the Austro-Hungarian Empire. Austria, with German
en|backing, tried to crush Serbia in 1914 but Russia intervened, thus igniting the First World
en|War in which Austria dissolved into nation states.In 1918, the region of Vojvodina proclaimed its
en|secession from Austria-Hungary to unite with the pan-Slavic State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs; the
en|Kingdom of Serbia joined the union on 1 December 1918, and the country was named
en|Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes. It was renamed Yugoslavia, which was never able to
en|tame the multiple nationalities and religions and it flew apart in civil war in the
en|1990s. Greece The Greek drive for independence from the Ottoman Empire inspired supporters across Christian
en|Europe, especially in Britain. France, Russia and Britain intervened to make this nationalist dream become
en|reality with the Greek War of Independence (1821-1829/1830). Bulgaria Bulgarian modern nationalism emerged under Ottoman
en|rule in the late 18th and early 19th century. An autonomous Bulgarian Exarchate was established
en|in 1870/1872 for the diocese of Bulgaria as well as for those, wherein at least
en|two-thirds of Orthodox Christians were willing to join it. The April Uprising in 1876 indirectly
en|resulted in the re-establishment of Bulgaria in 1878. Poland In the 1790s, Germany, Russia and
en|Austria partitioned Poland. Napoleon set up the Duchy of Warsaw, igniting a spirit of Polish
en|nationalism. Russia took it over in 1815 as Congress Poland with the tsar as King
en|of Poland. Large-scale nationalist revolts erupted in 1830 and 1863–64 but were harshly crushed by
en|Russia, which tried to Russify the Polish language, culture and religion. The collapse of the
en|Russian Empire in the First World War enabled the major powers to reestablish an independent
en|Second Polish Republic, which survived until 1939. Meanwhile, Poles in areas controlled by Germany moved
en|into heavy industry but their religion came under attack by Bismarck in the Kulturkampf of
en|the 1870s. The Poles joined German Catholics in a well-organized new Centre Party, and defeated
en|Bismarck politically. He responded by stopping the harassment and cooperating with the Centre Party. Spain
en|After the War of the Spanish Succession, the assimilation of the Crown of Aragon by
en|the Castilian Crown through the Decrees of Nova planta was the first step in the
en|creation of the Spanish nation state, through the imposition of the political and cultural characteristics
en|of the dominant ethnic group, in this case the Castilians, over those of other ethnic
en|groups, who became national minorities to be assimilated. Since the political unification of 1714, Spanish
en|assimilation policies towards Catalan-speaking territories (Catalonia, Valencia, the Balearic Islands, part of Aragon) and other
en|national minorities have been a historical constant. The nationalization process accelerated in the 19th century,
en|in parallel to the origin of Spanish nationalism, the social, political and ideological movement that
en|tried to shape a Spanish national identity based on the Castilian model, in conflict with
en|the other historical nations of the State. These nationalist policies, sometimes very aggressive, and still
en|in force, are the seed of repeated territorial conflicts within the State. Education An important
en|component of nationalism was the study of the nation's heritage, emphasizing the national language and
en|literary culture. This stimulated, and was in turn strongly supported by, the emergence of national
en|educational systems. Latin gave way to the national language, and compulsory education, with strong support
en|from modernizers and the media, became standard in Germany and eventually other West European nations.
en|Voting reforms extended the franchise. Every country developed a sense of national origins – the
en|historical accuracy was less important than the motivation toward patriotism. Universal compulsory education was extended
en|to girls at the elementary level. By the 1890s, strong movements emerged in some countries,
en|including France, Germany and the United States, to extend compulsory education to the secondary level.
en|Ideological coalitions After the defeat of revolutionary France, the great powers tried to restore the
en|situation which existed before 1789. The 1815 Congress of Vienna produced a peaceful balance of
en|power among the European empires, known as the Metternich system. The powerbase of their support
en|was the aristocracy. However, their reactionary efforts were unable to stop the spread of revolutionary
en|movements: the middle classes had been deeply influenced by the ideals of the French revolution,
en|and the Industrial Revolution brought important economical and social changes.Radical intellectuals looked to the working
en|classes for a base for socialist, communist and anarchistic ideas. Widely influential was the 1848
en|Communist Manifesto by Karl Marx and Friedrich Engels.The middle classes and businessmen promoted liberalism, free
en|trade and capitalism. Aristocratic elements concentrated in government service, the military and the established churches.
en|Nationalist movements (in Germany, Italy, Poland, Hungary, and elsewhere) sought national unification and/or liberation from
en|foreign rule. As a result, the period between 1815 and 1871 saw a large number
en|of revolutionary attempts and independence wars. Greece successfully revolted against Ottoman rule in the 1820s.
en|France under Napoleon III Napoleon III, nephew of Napoleon I, parlayed his famous name and
en|to widespread popularity across France. He returned from exile in 1848, promising to stabilize the
en|chaotic political situation. He was elected president and maneuvered successfully to name himself Emperor, a
en|move approved later by a large majority of the French electorate. The first part of
en|his Imperial term brought many important reforms, facilitated by Napoleon's control of the lawmaking body,
en|the government, and the French Armed Forces. Hundreds of old Republican leaders were arrested and
en|deported. Napoleon controlled the media and censored the news. In compensation for the loss of
en|freedom, Napoleon gave the people new hospitals and asylums, beautified and modernized Paris, and built
en|a modern railroad and transportation system that dramatically improved commerce. The economy grew, but industrialization
en|was not as rapid as Britain, and France depended largely on small family-oriented firms as
en|opposed to the large companies that were emerging in the United States and Germany. France
en|was on the winning side in the Crimean War (1854–56), but after 1858 Napoleon's foreign-policy
en|was less and less successful. Foreign-policy blunders finally destroyed his reign in 1870–71. His empire
en|collapsed after being defeated in the Franco-Prussian War.France became a republic, but until the 1880s
en|there was a strong popular demand for monarchy. Hostility to the Catholic Church became a
en|major issue, as France battle between secular and religious forces well into the 20th century,
en|with the secular elements usually more successful. The French Third Republic emerged in 1871. Bismarck's
en|Germany From his base in Prussia, Otto von Bismarck in the 1860s engineered a series
en|of short, decisive wars, that unified most of the German states (excluding Austria) into a
en|powerful German Empire. By 1871 he used balance of power diplomacy to preserve Germany's new
en|role and keep Europe at peace. The new German Empire industrialized rapidly and challenged Britain
en|for economic leadership. Bismarck was removed from office in 1890 by an aggressive young Kaiser
en|Wilhelm II, who pursued a disruptive foreign policy that polarized Europe into rival camps. These
en|rival camps went to war with each other in 1914. Austrian and Russian empires The
en|power of nationalism to create new states was irresistible in the 19th century, and the
en|process could lead to collapse in the absence of a strong nationalism. Austria-Hungary had the
en|advantage of size and a large army, but multiple disadvantages: rivals on four sides, unstable
en|finances, a fragmented population, a thin industrial base, and minimal naval resources. It did have
en|the advantage of good diplomats, typified by Metternich. They employed a grand strategy for survival
en|that balanced out different forces, set up buffer zones, and kept the Hapsburg empire going
en|despite wars with the Ottomans, Frederick the Great, Napoleon and Bismarck, until the First World
en|War. The Empire overnight disintegrated into multiple states based on ethnic nationalism and the principle
en|of self-determination.The Russian Empire likewise brought together a multitude of languages and cultures, so that
en|its military defeat in the First World War led to multiple splits that created independent
en|Finland, Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia, and Poland, and briefly independent Ukraine, Armenia, Georgia, and Azerbaijan. =
en|Imperialism = Colonial empires were the product of the European Age of Discovery from the
en|15th century. The initial impulse behind these dispersed maritime empires and those that followed was
en|trade. Both the Portuguese Empire and Spanish Empire quickly grew into the first global political
en|and economic systems with territories spread around the world. Subsequent major European colonial empires included
en|the French, Dutch, and British. The latter, consolidated during the period of British maritime hegemony
en|in the 19th century, became the largest empire in history because of the improved ocean
en|transportation technologies of the time as well as electronic communication. At its height in 1920,
en|the British Empire covered a quarter of the Earth's land area and comprised a quarter
en|of its population. Other European countries, such as Belgium, Germany, and Italy, pursued colonial empires
en|as well (mostly in Africa), but they were smaller. Russia built its Russian Empire through
en|conquest by land in Eastern Europe, and Asia. By the mid-19th century, the Ottoman Empire
en|had declined. This instigated the Crimean War in 1854 and began a tenser period of
en|minor clashes among the globe-spanning empires of Europe. In the second half of the 19th
en|century, the Kingdom of Sardinia and the Kingdom of Prussia carried out a series of
en|wars that resulted in the creation of Italy and Germany as nation-states, significantly changing the
en|balance of power in Europe. From 1870, Otto von Bismarck engineered a German hegemony that
en|put France in a critical situation. It slowly rebuilt its relationships, seeking alliances with Russia
en|and Britain to control the growing power of Germany. In this way, two opposing sides
en|– the Triple Alliance of 1882 (Germany, Austria-Hungary and Italy) and the Triple Entente of
en|1907 (Britain, France and Russia) – formed in Europe, escalating military forces and alliances. 1914–1945:
en|two world wars = World War I = After the relative peace of most of
en|the 19th century, the rivalry between European powers, compounded by rising nationalism among ethnic groups,
en|exploded in 1914, when the First World War started. Over 65 million European soldiers were
en|mobilised from 1914 to 1918; 20 million soldiers and civilians died. On one side were
en|Germany, Austria-Hungary, the Ottoman Empire and Bulgaria (the Central Powers/Triple Alliance), while on the other
en|side stood Serbia and the Triple Entente(France, Britain and Russia), which were joined by Italy
en|in 1915, Romania in 1916 and the United States in 1917. The Western Front involved
en|especially brutal combat without any territorial gains by either side. Single battles like Verdun and
en|the Somme killed hundreds of thousands. Czarist Russia collapsed in the February Revolution of 1917
en|and Germany claimed victory on the Eastern Front. After eight months of liberal rule, the
en|October Revolution brought Vladimir Lenin and the Bolsheviks to power, leading to the creation of
en|the Soviet Union. With American entry into the war in 1917, and the failure of
en|Germany's spring 1918 offensive, Germany had run out of manpower. Germany's allies, Austria-Hungary and the
en|Ottoman Empire, surrendered and dissolved, followed by Germany on 11 November 1918. The world war
en|was settled by the victors at the Paris Peace Conference, 1919. The major decisions were
en|the creation of the League of Nations; peace treaties with defeated enemies, most notably the
en|Treaty of Versailles with Germany; the awarding of German and Ottoman overseas possessions as "mandates",
en|chiefly to Britain and France; and the drawing of new national boundaries to better reflect
en|the forces of nationalism. Multiple nations were required to sign minority rights treaties. The Treaty
en|of Versailles itself weakened Germany's military power and placed full blame for the war and
en|costly reparations on its shoulders – the humiliation and resentment in Germany was probably one
en|of the causes of Nazi success and indirectly a cause of World War II. =
en|Interwar = In the Treaty of Versailles (1919) the winners recognised the new states (Poland,
en|Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Austria, Yugoslavia, Finland, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania) created in central Europe from the defunct
en|German, Austro-Hungarian and Russian empires, based on national (ethnic) self-determination. It was a peaceful era
en|with a few small wars before 1922 such as the Ukrainian–Soviet War (1917–1921) and the
en|Polish–Soviet War (1919–1921). Prosperity was widespread, and the major cities sponsored a youth culture called
en|the "Roaring Twenties" or "Jazz Age".The Allied victory in the First World War seemed to
en|mark the triumph of liberalism. Historian Martin Blinkhorn argues that the liberal themes were ascendant
en|in terms of "cultural pluralism, religious and ethnic toleration, national self-determination, free-market economics, representative and
en|responsible government, free trade, unionism, and the peaceful settlement of international disputes through a new
en|body, the League of Nations." However, as early as 1917, the emerging liberal order was
en|being challenged by the new communist movement. Communist revolts were beaten back everywhere else, but
en|succeeded in Russia. Italy adopted an authoritarian dictatorship known as Fascism in 1922. Authoritarian regimes
en|replaced democracy in the 1930s in Nazi Germany, Portugal, Austria, Poland, Greece, the Baltic countries
en|and Francoist Spain. By 1940, there were only four liberal democracies left on the European
en|continent: France, Finland, Switzerland and Sweden. = Great Depression: 1929–1939 = After the Wall Street
en|Crash of 1929, most of the world sank into a Great Depression; prices and profits
en|fell and unemployment soared. The worst hit sectors included heavy industry, export-oriented agriculture, mining and
en|lumbering, and construction. World trade fell by two-thirds.In most of Europe, many nations turned to
en|dictators and authoritarian regimes. The most momentous change of government came when Hitler took power
en|in Germany in 1933. The main institution that was meant to bring stability was the
en|League of Nations, created in 1919. However the League failed to resolve any major crises,
en|undermined by the bellicosity of Nazi Germany, Imperial Japan, the Soviet Union, and Mussolini's Italy,
en|and by the non-participation of the United States. By 1937 it was largely ignored.Italy conquered
en|Ethiopia in 1931. The Spanish Civil War (1936–1939) was won by the rebels (the Nationalist
en|faction), led by Francisco Franco. The civil war did not escalate into a larger conflict,
en|but did become a worldwide ideological battleground that pitted the left, the communist movement and
en|many liberals against Catholics, conservatives, and fascists. Britain, France and the US remained neutral. Worldwide
en|there was a decline in pacifism and a growing sense that another world war was
en|imminent. = World War II = In 1938 Adolf Hitler annexed the Sudetenland. In the
en|Munich Agreement, Britain and France adopted a policy of appeasement, but Germany subsequently took over
en|the rest of Czechoslovakia. After allying with Japan in the Anti-Comintern Pact and then also
en|with Benito Mussolini's Italy in the "Pact of Steel", and finally signing a non-aggression treaty
en|with the Soviet Union in August 1939, Hitler launched the Second World War on 1
en|September 1939 by attacking Poland. Britain and France declared war on Germany, but there was
en|little fighting during the "Phoney War" period. War began in earnest in spring 1940 with
en|the successful Blitzkrieg conquests of Denmark, Norway, the Low Countries, and France. Britain defeated Germany's
en|air attacks in the Battle of Britain. Hitler's goal was to control Eastern Europe but
en|the attack on the Soviet Union was delayed until June 1941 and the Wehrmacht was
en|stopped close to Moscow in December 1941.Over the next year the Germans started to suffer
en|a series of defeats. War raged between the Axis Powers (Germany, Italy, and Japan) and
en|the Allied Forces (British Empire, Soviet Union, and the United States). The Allied Forces won
en|in North Africa, invaded Italy in 1943, and recaptured France in 1944. In 1945 Germany
en|itself was invaded from the east by the Soviet Union and from the west by
en|the other Allies. As the Red Army conquered the Reichstag in the Battle of Berlin,
en|Hitler committed suicide and Germany surrendered. World War II was the deadliest conflict in human
en|history, causing between 50 and 80 million deaths, the majority of whom were civilians (approximately
en|38 to 55 million).This period was also marked by systematic genocide. In 1942–45, separately from
en|the war-related deaths, the Nazis killed over 11 million civilians identified through IBM-enabled censuses, including
en|the majority of the Jews and Gypsies of Europe, millions of Polish and Soviet Slavs,
en|homosexuals, Jehovah's Witnesses, disabled people, and political enemies. Meanwhile, in the 1930s the Soviet system
en|of forced labour, expulsions and allegedly engineered famine had a similar death toll. Millions of
en|civilians were affected by forced population transfers. Cold War era The world wars ended the
en|pre-eminent position of Britain, France and Germany in Europe and the world. At the Yalta
en|Conference, Europe was divided into spheres of influence between the victors of World War II,
en|and soon became the principal zone of contention in the Cold War between the Western
en|countries and the Communist bloc. The United States and the majority of European liberal democracies
en|established the NATO military alliance. Later, the Soviet Union and its satellites in 1955 established
en|the Warsaw Pact. The Warsaw Pact had a much larger ground force, but the American-French-British
en|nuclear umbrellas protected NATO. Communist states were imposed by the Red Army in the East,
en|while parliamentary democracy became dominant in the West. Most historians point to its success as
en|the product of exhaustion with war and dictatorship, and the promise of continued economic prosperity.
en|= Economic recovery = The United States gave away about $20 billion in Marshall Plan
en|grants and other funding to Western Europe, 1945 to 1951. Historian Michael J. Hogan argues
en|that American aid was critical in stabilizing the economy and politics of Western Europe. It
en|brought in modern management that dramatically increased productivity, and encouraged cooperation between labor and management,
en|and among states. Local Communist parties were opposed, and they lost prestige and influence and
en|a role in government. In strategic terms, says Hogan, the Marshall Plan strengthened the West
en|against the possibility of a communist invasion or political takeover. However, the Marshall Plan's role
en|in the rapid recovery has been debated. Most reject the idea that it only miraculously
en|revived Europe, since the evidence shows that a general recovery was already under way. Economic
en|historians Bradford De Long and Barry Eichengreen conclude: It was not large enough to have
en|significantly accelerated recovery by financing investment, aiding the reconstruction of damaged infrastructure, or easing commodity
en|bottlenecks. We argue, however, that the Marshall Plan did play a major role in setting
en|the stage for post-World War II Western Europe's rapid growth. The conditions attached to Marshall
en|Plan aid pushed European political economy in a direction that left its post World War
en|II "mixed economies" with more "market" and less "controls" in the mix.The Soviet Union concentrated
en|on its own recovery. It seized and transferred most of Germany's industrial plants and it
en|exacted war reparations from East Germany, Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria. It used trading arrangements deliberately
en|designed to favor the Soviet Union. Moscow controlled the Communist parties that ruled the satellite
en|states. Historian Mark Kramer concludes: The net outflow of resources from eastern Europe to the
en|Soviet Union was approximately $15 billion to $20 billion in the first decade after World
en|War II, an amount roughly equal to the total aid provided by the United States
en|to western Europe under the Marshall Plan.Looking at the half century after the war historian
en|Walter Lacquer concluded: "The postwar generations of European elites aimed to create more democratic societies.
en|They wanted to reduce the extremes of wealth and poverty and provide essential social services
en|in a way that prewar generations had not. They had had quite enough of unrest
en|and conflict. For decades many Continental societies had more or less achieved these aims and
en|had every reason to be proud of their progress. Europe was quiet and civilized. Europe's
en|success was based on recent painful experience: the horrors of two world wars; the lessons
en|of dictatorship; the experiences of fascism and communism. Above all, it was based on a
en|feeling of European identity and common values – or so it appeared at the time."The
en|post-war period witnessed a significant rise in the standard of living of the Western European
en|working class.Western Europe's industrial nations in the 1970s were hit by a global economic crisis.
en|Causes included obsolescent heavy industry, sudden high energy prices which caused sharp inflation, inefficient nationalized
en|railways and heavy industries, lagging computer technology, high government deficits and growing unrest led by
en|militant labour unions. Germany and Sweden sought to create a social consensus behind a gradual
en|restructuring. Germany's efforts proved highly successful. In Britain under the premiership of Margaret Thatcher, the
en|solution was shock therapy, high interest rates, austerity, and selling off inefficient corporations as well
en|as the public housing. One result was escalating social tensions in Britain. Thatcher eventually defeated
en|her opponents and radically changed the British economy, but controversy persisted. Recent history Western Europe
en|began economic and then political integration, with the aim to unite the region and defend
en|it. This process included organisations such as the European Coal and Steel Community and the
en|Council of Europe. The Solidarność movement in the 1980s weakened the Communist government in Poland.
en|At the time the Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev initiated perestroika and glasnost, which weakened Soviet
en|influence in Europe. In 1989 after the Pan-European Picnic the Iron Curtain and the Berlin
en|Wall came down and Communist governments outside the Soviet Union were deposed. In 1990 the
en|Federal Republic of Germany absorbed East Germany. In 1991 the Communist Party of the Soviet
en|Union in Moscow collapsed, ending the USSR, which split into fifteen independent states. The most
en|violent dissolution happened in Yugoslavia. Four out of six Yugoslav republics declared independence and for
en|most of them a violent war ensued, in some parts lasting until 1995. In 2006
en|Montenegro seceded and became an independent state. Kosovo's government unilaterally declared independence from Serbia on
en|17 February 2008. The European Economic Community pushed for closer integration, co-operation in foreign and
en|home affairs, and started to increase its membership into the neutral and former communist countries.
en|In 1993, the Maastricht Treaty established the European Union, succeeding the EEC. The neutral countries
en|of Austria, Finland and Sweden acceded to the EU, and those that didn't join were
en|tied into the EU's economic market via the European Economic Area. These countries also entered
en|the Schengen Agreement which lifted border controls between member states. The euro was created in
en|1999 and replaced all previous currencies in participating states in 2002, forming the eurozone. The
en|EU did not participate in the Yugoslav Wars, and was divided on supporting the United
en|States in the 2003–2011 Iraq War. NATO was part of the war in Afghanistan, but
en|at a much lower level of involvement than the United States. In the post–Cold War
en|era, NATO and the EU have been gradually admitting most of the former members of
en|the Warsaw Pact. In 2004, the EU gained 10 new members. (Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania,
en|which had been part of the Soviet Union; Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland, Slovakia, and Slovenia,
en|five former-communist countries; Malta, and the divided island of Cyprus.) These were followed by Bulgaria
en|and Romania in 2007. Russia's regime interpreted these expansions as violations against NATO's promise to
en|not expand "one inch to the east" in 1990. Russia engaged in bilateral disputes about
en|gas supplies with Belarus and Ukraine which endangered the European supply, and engaged in a
en|war with Georgia in 2008. Public opinion in the EU turned against enlargement, partially due
en|to what was seen as over-eager expansion including Turkey gaining candidate status. The European Constitution
en|was rejected in France and the Netherlands, and then (as the Treaty of Lisbon) in
en|Ireland, although a second vote passed in Ireland in 2009. The financial crisis of 2007–08
en|affected Europe, and government responded with austerity measures. Limited ability of the smaller EU nations
en|(most notably Greece) to handle their debts led to social unrest, government liquidation, and financial
en|insolvency. In May 2010, the German parliament agreed to loan 22.4 billion euros to Greece
en|over three years, with the stipulation that Greece follow strict austerity measures. See European sovereign-debt
en|crisis. Beginning in 2014, Ukraine has been in a state of revolution and unrest. On
en|16 March, a disputed referendum was held in Crimea leading to the de facto secession
en|of Crimea and its largely internationally unrecognized annexation to the Russian Federation. In June 2016,
en|in a referendum in the United Kingdom on the country's membership in the European Union,
en|52% of voters voted to leave the EU, leading to the complex Brexit separation process
en|and negotiations, which led to political and economic changes for both the UK and the
en|remaining European Union countries. The UK left the EU on 31 January 2020. Later that
en|year, Europe was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic. According to the Wall Street Journal in
en|2021 as Angela Merkel stepped down as Chancellor of Germany after 16 years: Ms. Merkel
en|leaves in her wake a weakened Europe, a region whose aspirations to act as a
en|third superpower have come to seem ever more unrealistic. When she became chancellor in 2005,
en|the EU was at a high point: It had adopted the euro, which was meant
en|to rival the dollar as a global currency, and had just expanded by absorbing former
en|members of the Soviet bloc. Today’s EU, by contrast, is geographically and economically diminished. Having
en|lost the U.K. because of Brexit, it faces deep political and cultural divisions, lags behind
en|in the global race for innovation and technology and is increasingly squeezed by the mounting
en|U.S.-China strategic rivalry. Europe has endured thanks in part to Ms. Merkel’s pragmatic stewardship, but
en|it has been battered by crises during her entire time in office.Russia began an invasion
en|of Ukraine on 24 February 2022, in a major escalation of the Russo-Ukrainian War that
en|began in 2014. It is the largest conventional military attack in Europe since World War
